<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Finance &amp; The Family: Can house prices get off the floor? -
John Authers asks if the market is set to recover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GHASTLY hush has fallen on the housing market. Investors, homeowners and
potential homebuyers are standing back, waiting to see if house prices can
take off again.
The silence, compared with previous loudly proclaimed false dawns, is
because everything that can be done to stimulate the market has already been
done. If the housing market followed the same economic rules as other
markets, it would already have recovered. But houses have special
characteristics, which fuelled house price inflation at the end of the
1980s, and which might stifle recovery.
Potential first-time buyers have access to historically low interest rates
and house prices which have dropped sharply since the boom of 1988. In the
last two decades, houses have rarely been cheaper in proportion to income.
If they buy a house for between Pounds 30,000 and Pounds 60,000, the Budget
has relieved them of the burden of 1 per cent stamp duty.
House prices are sending confusing signals. The Halifax house price index
fell in the first two months of this year, logging an overall annual fall of
7.2 per cent. But the Nationwide index rose 1 per cent in March.
Further possible bad news comes from the Adams Residential Property Index,
which is compiled by James R Adams, a market research consultancy, by
monitoring housing completions made by solicitors. It shows completions at
an all-time low of 59,963 for February. This is usually the worst month of
the year for completions - but last year, the figure was 69,943, and in 1991
it was 83,150. In 1989, it was more than 100,000.
Optimists about the property market can call on figures released by the
Halifax building society, the UK's biggest lender, in evidence. Halifax says
that Halifax Property Services, its estate agency, had its best month for
two years in February, although the sales it made will not be reflected in
completions figures for some months.
Halifax's research of potential first-time buyers found that since July last
year, when base rates were at 10 per cent, 34 per cent more were seriously
considering buying, including 130 per cent more of those currently renting.
Other lenders report a similar experience. Abbey National and Nationwide
have had increased applications, which have yet to convert into sales. If
all these people go through with their purchases, the housing market could
at last have the volume to fuel a recovery in house prices.
Whether they do so will depend on confidence. People need to believe in the
housing market before it can pick up again. John Ginnarlis, of PA Consulting
Group, says there used to be two separate demands for housing: as a
commodity and as an investment. After several years of falling prices,
people only want property as a commodity.
Can the market ever recover, given that confidence has taken such a blow?
Joe Egerton, of Economic and Regulatory Analysts, points to extra structural
difficulties. First is the problem of 'negative equity' - when the value of
your house would not pay the costs of paying off the loan. Once transaction
costs and high mortgage indemnity premiums are taken into account, many
people who could sell their house for more than the outstanding mortgage
have a disincentive against moving.
The bubble of people who bought at a younger age than they would normally
have done deprives the market of its usual quota of first-time buyers. The
people who would normally have fuelled a recovery are instead 'well and
truly locked in,' said Egerton.
A survey by NOP shows that in the six months to September last year,
first-time buyers made up 34 per cent of the new mortgage market. In the
boom-time of 1987, they accounted for 56 per cent of mortgages.
On a practical level, Egerton points out that many of the conversions and
other cheap properties bought to 'get on the housing ladder' in 1988 are now
in poor condition and, therefore, harder to sell. Many of these properties
have moved into a rental 'black market', let at low prices to friends, of
the owners, making reliable statistics of the rental market impossible to
compile.
Egerton says, 'there definitely is a recovery in sales,' but this applies
only to quality properties at reasonable prices. Even this is an improvement
on a year ago. However, Egerton's arguments suggest that a repeat of the
boom of 1988 is impossible - the demand does not exist to sustain it.
James Morrell, economic adviser for Charterhouse, has a more positive view.
He believes that increased volume is important in pushing house prices up.
'There's about a year's time lag between the change in volume of
transactions and a change in house prices,' he says.
On that basis, this could be a good time to buy, as the bottom may have been
reached. The figures for volume look like a trough, and may be followed by
greater activity if the cautious report from lenders are correct. Morrell is
confident: 'People who are planning to go into the market would be a bit
unwise to dither much longer.'
Even so, a small recovery this year would leave prices at the same level
they reached in 1992 - therefore showing a loss, in real terms, once
inflation is taken into account. Housing still does not make sense as
investment alone, and poor quality housing, as many of the buyers of 1988
would agree, should be avoided.
</TEXT>
<XX>
