<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Finance &amp; The Family: How to pay off a home loan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW should you repay a mortgage?
The answer pushed by the financial services industry over the last few years
is that you should not repay it directly, but put money towards an
investment as collateral. Over 25 years, you pay just the interest on the
loan and repay the capital only at the end of that time. According to Adams
RPI, 63.1 per cent of mortgages taken out last year were backed by an
endowment, while 33.7 per cent were capital repayment. In 1988, the
imbalance was even greater: 75.9 per cent against 21.3 per cent.
The argument against capital repayment mortgages is that very little of the
capital is repaid in the early years. Given that homeowners move house every
six years on average, they may find that they have made little progress
towards paying off the debt. With an endowment policy or other savings
mechanism, you are always making progress towards that repayment date.
Furthermore, to the extent that mortgage interest relief survives, it is
more tax efficient to pay interest than to repay capital.
However, this argument only makes sense if the savings scheme is maintained
for the full 25 years. Sadly, this seems not to be the case. Most mortgage
endowments are not maintained until maturity, meaning that penal surrender
values are imposed on the borrower.
If you need to reduce payments for any reason, repayment mortgages offer a
simple method - you can just stop repaying capital for a while. With
interest-only mortgages, it should be easy to stop contributing money to the
savings vehicle. But you cannot stop paying premiums into an endowment
without suffering a severe penalty. This inflexibility tips the balance
decisively against endowments - not only are you taking a risk by not paying
off the loan, you are also tying yourself to that course, come what may.
Another option is the personal pension mortgage, where only interest is paid
on the home loan and premiums are paid into a pension plan. The capital is
repaid out of the cash-free sum you are granted on retirement. Personal
pensions are the most tax-efficient investment vehicle for backing a
mortgage, as all contributions are invested gross into an untaxed fund. But
they are also the least flexible - you could find yourself spending most of
your retirement cash on finally completing your house purchase, rather than
investing it to provide greater freedom in retirement.
More flexible collective investment vehicles, such as unit and investment
trusts, allow you to stop payments without penalty. Top-rate taxpayers, in
particular, can buy them very tax-efficiently through Peps (personal equity
plans). But Pep mortgages accounted for only 0.1 per cent of last year's
total.
The safest option is capital repayment, particularly for those buying a home
for life. Those who expect to move frequently and are prepared to take some
care over their investments should get better value from an interest-only
mortgage, linked to a Pep or investment trust savings scheme. As life
assurance can be obtained separately at fairly low cost, there is little to
be said in favour of the endowment mortgage.
</TEXT>
