<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Finance &amp; The Family: Getting into a fix
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIXED rate mortgages have grown in popularity compared with variable rates
over the last few months, writes John Authers.
There is good reason for this. In general, a fixed rate should be preferable
when base rates are set to rise; variable rates give a better chance of
catching a fall.
However, fixed mortgages carry some dangers. First is the arrangement fee -
typically around Pounds 200 - which is often non-refundable. Over a long
period this should still leave you with a saving, but if the mortgage is
only fixed for a year, the benefits may be low.
Then there are package deals. Some lenders have a lower arrangement fee, but
oblige you to buy their own insurance policy. These are almost always at
higher premiums than you could find by shopping around.
You should also beware of strings tied to the repayment mechanism. Some only
offer a fixed rate if you back it with either an endowment or a personal
pension - and neither is generally suitable.
Particularly attractive offers available at present, according to Money
Facts, include 7.95 per cent fixed for five years from Cheltenham &amp;
Gloucester, which can be taken on an interest-only basis with no extra
insurance; 7.9 per cent fixed until March 31 1998 from Britannia (buildings
and contents insurance is required); and 7.7 per cent from Credit Agricole,
where buildings and contents insurance is required.
Availability of funds poses another argument in favour of fixing. As Weekend
FT readers will know, savings rates from building societies are low at
present, and many savers have withdrawn funds to invest elsewhere. This
makes sense for the saver, but it removes the funds which the building
societies use to back mortgages. This could force mortgage rates up, making
the current fixed rates look better value.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
