</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Markets: Bank puts a new gloss on gilts - Serious Money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GILTS HAVE been neglected by the private investor for understandable
reasons. Too often, inflation has destroyed their value; and they are
difficult to comprehend and buy.
It is true there is a cheap service available at the Post Office. But it is
hardly user friendly: you must queue, there are no specialist staff to help
and it is up to you to decide between the Exchequer 12 1/2 pc 1994 and the
Treasury 9 3/4 pc 2002.
So it is good news that the Bank of England has produced a booklet* with the
aim of giving investors basic information about the gilts market. This
desire to educate is not entirely altruistic; the government may have some
Pounds 50bn of gilts to sell this year and private investors are a large
potential market.
The booklet is a useful guide for beginners, although it does not answer
some of the questions that readers often ask the FT, such as how to
calculate the real yield on an index-linked gilt. Nor is the section on the
taxation of accrued interest clear.
It is a complex area. The price of gilts bought between dividend entitlement
dates includes an element to reflect the accrued interest. If you have
holdings of less than Pounds 5,000, you may find yourself paying income tax
on this accrued element, even though you have paid for it out of capital.
Say you pay Pounds 1,025 for stock reflecting accrued interest of Pounds 25
out of a forthcoming dividend of Pounds 50. You will pay income tax on
Pounds 50, not the Pounds 25 you receive.
But there is a more fundamental question, which the guide does not address.
Bond prices have been rising steadily since the start of 1991 - so is the
government encouraging investors to buy gilts at the peak of the market? Don
Smith of Greenwell Montagu does not think so. He believes that long bond
yields, currently around 8.5 per cent, will fall to 7 3/4 per cent. Since
yields and prices have an inverse relationship, that means gilt prices will
rise.
Greenwell Montagu believes that fears of renewed inflation are overdone. It
expects a rate of 3.25 per cent at the year end, which means that gilts are
trading on attractive real yields of more than 5 per cent.
Those who are not as optimistic as Greenwell Montagu about inflation might
prefer index-linked gilts, which merit two pages of their own in the Bank of
England guide. Both income and repayment values increase in line with the
RPI. However, the trading price does not always rise in line with the RPI,
which is what can cause investors so much confusion. Again, this is not made
clear in the guide.
One practical measure announced this week was an increase in the maximum
that can be invested in gilts via the National Savings Stock Register (at
the Post Office) in any one gilt. This has been increased from Pounds 10,000
to Pounds 25,000 per day. In future, all stocks will be available rather
than just a selection (both changes apply from April 7.) Although you may
not get the best price via the NSSR, dealing costs are cheap (Pounds 1 for
the first Pounds 250, then 50p for every further Pounds 125 or part
thereof). Buying Pounds 25,000 of stock would thus cost Pounds 100.
What the guide cannot tell you is which are the best issues to buy. This
depends on your individual circumstances; need for income, tax position and
so on. It may be worthwhile paying extra in commission to get the benefit of
a stockbroker's advice on this. Greenwell Montagu says private investors are
normally keen to buy issues which are trading below par and have shifted
their attention to the longer end of the market.
Investing in Gilts; a guide for the small investor. Available in 1,500 post
offices or from the Bank of England, PO Box 96, Gloucester, GL1 1YB,
freephone 0800-616814.
S G WARBURG'S new quarterly review of income shares adds further fuel to the
debate about this extremely complex sector. Referring to the so-called
'ordinary income shares' (those with a repayment value which is not set, but
is dependent on the growth of the trust's assets), Warburg says 'at current
levels, the sector is cheap, assuming 5 per cent growth rates in capital and
dividends.'
The shares which Warburg recommends as a result of its analysis are: Fleming
International High; Gartmore American; M&amp;G Income Geared Units; Rights &amp;
Issues Capital: Drayton Blue Chip: Kleinwort High: and River &amp; Mercantile
Extra. These offer gross redemption yields of between 14 and 20 per cent, if
one assumes the trusts' assets and income grow at 5 per cent per annum until
maturity.
However, this does not mean the share prices will grow substantially.
Because of the high dividend income, these shares stand above their
repayment values were the trusts to be wound up today.
Warburg points out that, in some cases, 5 per cent growth in assets will be
needed for investors to get their capital back at redemption. Accordingly,
the return on these trusts is largely in the form of income, which may have
disadvantageous tax consequences for higher rate payers.
This is a sector of the market which should be limited to the very assiduous
amateur investor, and only then with expert advice. The rest would be safer
with the likes of Foreign &amp; Colonial.
</TEXT>
<XX>
