<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / The Long View: While bankers sleep
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANKERS have withdrawn defensively into their parlours, but the sins
they committed as they naively explored the red light districts of late
1980s finance are still troubling them.
This week a string of leading banks faced losing half the Pounds 1bn or more
they advanced in 1989 to support Isosceles, an unquoted supermarket buyout
vehicle which owns the Gateway chain. It was notable for importing concepts
of financial engineering such as mezzanine debt and 'stub' equity (which
even at the time some people unkindly pointed out was an anagram of 'bust').
Now the stores group cannot possibly pay the interest on its mountain of
debt and a financial restructuring is under way. More trouble looms at
Queens Moat Houses, another Pounds 1bn-plus borrower, which asked for a
share price suspension on Wednesday 'pending clarification of the company's
financial position'.
While the banks struggle, and their most troublesome clients are still on
life support, the UK corporate sector as a whole is nevertheless getting its
financial affairs back into passably decent shape. In 1989 and 1990 the
industrial and commercial company sector was running alarming financial
deficits of around Pounds 20bn a year, but that was cut to Pounds 10bn by
1992 and there should be a surplus in the current year, the first since
1987.
The balance sheet of the corporate sector is looking somewhat better
structured, too. At the peak in the late 1980s companies were borrowing more
than Pounds 30bn a year from banks, but in 1991 and 1992 there were actually
small net repayments. Rights issues are already flowing, and confirmation of
economic recovery will bring out many more; in addition, there could be an
active market for new company flotations this year. Elsewhere, big companies
are heavy issuers of Eurosterling bonds. Such capital market refinancing is
good for the corporate sector, but it leaves the banks with a quality
problem: the good loans are being repaid but the bad ones stay on the books.
Five years ago banks dominated the financial markets, and prices of the
kinds of assets they liked to finance rocketed. This applied especially to
property, including hotels, as well as to fringe assets such as Van Goghs.
The banks rarely intruded into the stock market except to finance the
activities of takeover kings in buying companies from investors, which often
happened at up to twice the normal market price. The displaced investors, if
they were wise, put their money on deposit at high interest rates, and
waited.
Now the banks are out of the game and the securities markets are back in
control. Markets in shares, which offer the prospect of rising incomes,
especially attractive to investors such as pension funds, are very high.
Because of the shift in power, takeovers are almost dead: British companies
spent Pounds 1.6bn on the securities of other companies in 1992 compared
with Pounds 18bn in 1989. UK real estate remains stuck in the doldrums as
institutional investors ignore the bogus asset values generated some years
ago by bank finance and look at rental income which is no longer rising but
is flat at best and may fall at the ends of the leases. In the past four
years UK share prices have climbed by 30 per cent, but office property
values, according to Hillier Parker, have fallen by about 35 per cent.
Arguably the opposite kind of value distortion is now present, because
investors - intoxicated by a bull market - are too optimistic about the
extent to which dividends may grow.
There is now a cyclical opportunity for the stock market to extend its reach
down into the smaller company sector. Already the shares of small
capitalisation listed companies have been outperforming. The FT-SE SmallCap
Index is up 14 per cent so far in 1993 while the Footsie index of the 100
leaders has stagnated. So the beleaguered Stock Exchange could have been
over-hasty in threatening last month to shut down its Unlisted Securities
Market, a decision which anyway it appears to have deferred.
While the banks lick their wounds and busy themselves plugging the holes in
their balance sheet ratios there is inevitably concern that shortage of
finance for small and medium-sized companies might threaten the pace of
Britain's economic recovery. In fact this does not seem likely to be a
problem across the middle of the market where there is a variety of sources
of capital led by institutions such as 3i. According to 3i its dividend
income from this sector is still rising, which does not suggest any great
general distress. Meanwhile there is plenty of activity in restructuring
balance sheets, though little sign of demand for capital to finance
expansion of capacity.
But life is much tougher at the very small end, where hundreds of thousands
of 1980s Thatcherite entrepreneurs set themselves up in business with equity
released from overmortgaged homes and floating rate loans from clearing
banks, which jacked up the interest rate from 10 to 18 per cent by 1989.
This is the main source of the frightening statistics of business collapses.
Yet although many sole traders are still going bankrupt the number of
failures of limited companies is starting to tail off.
The combination of wild fluctuations in economic conditions together with
dependence upon floating rate finance is lethal. Somehow an institutional
framework for channelling fixed rate and equity finance to the smallest
businesses needs to be developed, but nobody can see how to make a profit
out of it. It was a vacuum that the clearing banks tried to fill in a way
that they now regret. Losing money did not even make them popular.
But it is astonishing how cycles swing and fortunes fluctuate. Perhaps those
shrewd investors should be reading the commercial estate agents' brochures,
although it is surely too soon to be considering a dabble in flower
paintings by one-eared Dutch painters.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
