<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / The thin blue line that divides Cambodia's killers: Nicholas
Woodsworth sees how the United Nations - and the Royal Navy - are trying to
keep the warring factions under control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS WOODSWORTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS an old floating cinema, made of wood and perched on a raft of
bamboo trunks, that sits anchored at the slow-swirling mouth of the Tonle
Sap lake in central Cambodia. Potted palms remain at either side of the
landing bay where film-goers used to tie up.
But the seats have been removed and the projectionist has found work
elsewhere: the place is under new management. On top of the cinema's tin
roof, now gleaming white, the letters 'UN' have been painted in figures 6ft
high.
If you stand on the old cinema's roof terrace, where a blue United Nations'
flag flies beside a Union Jack, you might think terra firma had never
existed. Now a military observer's naval patrol base, the floating building
sits lost on a wide flood plain where there is little distinction between
water and land.
This is a world of backed-up lake and flooded forest, swampy islands,
mirror-smooth creeks, and narrow channels of brown water that lose
themselves in endless braids and kinks. It is low and green and an easy
place in which to get lost. All life - plant, animal and human - has become
amphibious.
Just a stone's throw from the UN post, across a little inlet, begins the
settlement of Chhnok Tru. A village of 5,000 people, it has the sort of
amenities many back-country Cambodian towns lack: houses and hairdressers,
hardware and vegetable markets, medical stores, motor repair shops, eating
houses, temples, and bars.
In spite of its size, Chhnok Tru is not marked on any maps. It cannot be,
for the simple reason that it never stays put in any one place. Its houses
are as mobile as the boats that cruise its main thoroughfares. An entire
palm-thatched fishing community floating on bamboo, its location changes
according to the season and the rise and fall of the monsoon-fed lake.
Chhnok Tru is unusual for another reason. Half its population is ethnic
Vietnamese. Some of these immigrants arrived after Vietnam invaded Cambodia
in 1979, toppled its brutal Khmer Rouge revolutionary government, and
installed a regime controlled by Hanoi. Others, seeking jobs, living space
and economic opportunity they cannot find in over-crowded Vietnam, have
arrived only recently. Today all ethnic Vietnamese in Cambodia are special
targets for Khmer Rouge guerrillas who have made their repatriation one of
the pre-conditions to participation in UN-sponsored initiatives for peace
and democratic elections.
In March, in the bloodiest massacre since the UN began peace-keeping
operations here, 38 ethnic Vietnamese were gunned down by the Khmer Rouge in
Phum Chong Keas, another floating village on the Tonle Sap 75 kms from
Chhnok Tru.
What are UN peacekeepers up against in Cambodia? Seen from the capital,
Phnom Penh, UN operations here are a confused tangle of accusations and
counter-accusations. All too often, critics say, bureaucratic unwieldiness,
a lack of long-term perspective and the demands of political compromise have
sapped the UN's will to enforce a difficult mandate. I went to Chhnok Tru to
see what it was like, not for the administrator in his office but for the
peacekeeper on the ground - or, rather, the water. Seen from a boat deck on
the Tonle Sap, Cambodia's problems take on a different dimension.
BRITAIN'S Royal Navy has employed a bizarre fleet of water craft over the 12
months it has taken part in UN peace-keeping exercises in Cambodia. In this
sector of its operations, it has collected an old Vietnamese military
landing craft that looks like a steel shoe-box; two Russian 'Kanos' - cabin
cruiser-size, water-impelled jet boats that roar along in a stink of diesel;
and a nippy new runabout that slaps across the water with a 70 horse-power
engine at its stern. But most of the work of the Royal Navy military
observers here is done in little 10ft Zodiac inflatable dinghies. They are
not quite as toy-like as they seem; flat-bottomed and fast, they can
negotiate the shallow channels, strong currents and the thousand
surface-suspended fishing nets that make boating here such a tricky
business.
It was into one of these craft that I piled with several British sailors one
evening after I had arrived at 'Tango Hotel,' the call-sign of the floating
UN post. Our destination, 'Whisky Hotel,' lay not far away among the boats
of Chhnok Tru.
Whisky Hotel is pretty much what it says it is: a bar. The beer is cold, the
lighting dim, the music acceptable and the service comes with a smile. If
you smile back, the Vietnamese women who run it will spend entire evenings
shelling for you the dishes of dried watermelon seeds that come with the
drinks.
I was more or less prepared for the slight bobbing motion of the floating
bar. I was not unnerved by the sudden list it took when we seated ourselves
to one side of the room. Nor was I fazed by the water that began lapping at
our feet under our table. But I was not prepared for the company that, soon
after, sat down at a table opposite us.
CHHNOK TRU sits just below the bottom end of a large salient of Khmer
Rouge-controlled territory that tapers down from the borders of northern
Cambodia. This is an uneasy area of banditry, intimidation, extortion of the
weak, and a continuing low-level war between two of Cambodia's four warring
factions: CPAF, the ragged army of the Phnom Penh government, and the NADK,
the forces of the Khmer Rouge. Here, just about everyone - uniformed
soldiers, village militiamen, provincial government officials, Cambodian
fishermen, Vietnamese immigrants - goes about their business armed.
The CPAF soldiers who boarded the bar seemed as threatening as the boat in
which they arrived. It was narrow, low-slung and fast. Long pipes and intake
valves protruded from an uncovered engine that might have been winched out
of a '56 Chevy. It looked like something dreamed up by an American teenage
garage mechanic with a weekend sideline in hot rods. Only the tripod-mounted
light machine-gun at the bow hinted at more serious intent.
The soldiers swaggered in, dropped two AK-47 Kalashnikovs on the table and
started serious work on a bottle of Mekong whiskey. I felt less than
comfortable, but I had not reckoned with the professional skills of
28-year-old Royal Marine leading hand David Leng. A handshake, a few words
of kitchen Cambodian and soon he was spinning the chambers of .38
German-made revolver the smiling CPAF men brought out for him to admire.
Leng and the other men at Tango Hotel have an easy-going nonchalance that
veils a good amount of self-discipline and level-headedness. Both qualities
are much needed around Chhnok Tru. A large part of the UN military
observer's exercise here is two-way diplomacy: getting to know and inspire
confidence in two sides without appearing to favour either one. It is the
only way unarmed observers can hope to stand between adversaries and try to
create an atmosphere of reconciliation without getting shot at.
In reality, it is rarely that simple. The week before I arrived, Lt Cmdr
Alex Manning, senior officer at Tango Hotel, cruised northward up the Stoeng
Sen river from Chhnok Tru. He was attempting to deliver a letter inviting
the local Khmer Rouge commander to friendly discussions with the UN. The
Khmer Rouge not only took the letter, but him as well. Release came only
after three long and uncertain days.
The 10 UN observers at Chhnok Tru - seven Britons of the navy and marines,
two Filipinos and a Chilean - get on with a job as best they can. Over the
next few days, I accompanied them on the missions that make up a steady
routine of difficult and sometimes risky work.
Using the Kanos, we travelled to an isolated village 30 miles up the vast
Tonle Sap lake to assist in voter registration, a preliminary to
UN-supervised elections planned for May. In the Zodiacs, we patrolled
backwaters and narrow channels, visited local militias, dropped in on
government posts, talked to fishermen, inspected cargoes, and trailed along
behind river-boats where plump, Buddha-like captains sat smiling behind
their machine-guns.
THE MEN OF the Royal Navy are thorough professionals. They complain neither
about difficult local conditions nor the political decisions made by the UN
leadership in Phnom Penh and New York. But no one can avoid seeing that, by
the nature of the mandate handed to them, many of the 20,000 UN personnel in
Cambodia find their work frustrating and ineffective.
There is a strong sense on the ground that the leadership of Untac - the
United Nations Transitional Authority in Cambodia - has taken too
conciliatory a stance, not just with the Khmer Rouge but with all violators
of the Cambodian cease-fire and peace accords signed in 1991.
One soldier I met at a UN post south of Chhnok Tru put it bluntly: 'The UN
is doing a crap job. What we should be doing is taking guns away from the
nobbers who are shooting people. But all we are allowed to do is request
them to voluntarily surrender their arms. It is like going up to a bear and
politely asking him for his honey.'
The failure of the arms containment plan agreed on by Cambodia's factions is
just one of the frustrations. Cruise up any waterway around Chhnok Tru and
you will find some of the other problems faced every day by ordinary
Cambodians.
At riverside military check-points, CPAF soldiers demand money from
travellers. In the maze of fishing nets out on the lake, corrupt government
administrators extort both catches and money from fishermen. Phnom Penh
officials arrive every four or five days to relieve residents of floating
villages of much of their earnings. In some areas, villagers have to pay off
not only CPAF but the Khmer Rouge as well. The levels of extortion are so
high that many Cambodians seem not to care about which political group
controls them - only about how much they have to be paid.
IN SPITE of the fact that such armed intimidation falls under a UN mandate
for the enforcement of human rights, there is often little military
observers can do. The Khmer Rouge refuses the UN access to its areas.
Elsewhere, incidents can be noted, names taken, serial numbers of arms
recorded. But in a situation of growing unrest and factional violence,
effective civilian government has been all but obliterated. No doubt
UN-supervised elections will take place at some future date. But none of
this bodes well for their free-ness or fairness, nor for political stability
in their aftermath.
But the Royal Navy at Chhnok Tru never says die. On the last day of my stay,
a week after he had been detained on the Stoeng Sen, Alex Manning took David
Leng and me up the river again to investigate Khmer Rouge advances on
CPAF-held territory. We arrived minutes after Khmer Rouge soldiers had
rocketed a CPAF front-line post.
While a CPAF river patrol boat moved up its own Russian B-10 rocket
launcher, soldiers in ragged shirts and flip-flops huddled on the riverbank
cradling grenade launchers. But we saw no fighting; the Khmer Rouge had
melted back into the bush.
What can be done to stop sporadic guerrilla attacks in south-east Asia (or,
indeed, full-scale battles in south-east Europe)? Regardless of their best
intentions, UN forces in Cambodia can be only as effective as their own
leadership and the adversaries involved will allow them to be. We asked
questions, took notes, and listened to protests that it was the other side
that had started it first. Then we headed back down the winding, green river
to Chhnok Tru.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>KHZ  Kampuchea, Asia.
</CN>
