<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / West to reschedule Dollars 15bn of Russian debt: Eve of
summit deal offers boost for Yeltsin reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON, DAVID BUCHAN and ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, PARIS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN CREDITOR nations yesterday moved to bolster the position of Mr Boris
Yeltsin and Moscow's beleaguered reformers by agreeing to reschedule the
bulk of Russia's estimated Dollars 20bn (Pounds 14bn) debt service
obligations due this year.
The agreement comes on the eve of this weekend's US-Russian summit between
Mr Yeltsin and US president Bill Clinton in Vancouver. The summit will
focus, for the first time in the history of great power summitry, on
economic and financial rather than military and security issues.
Yesterday's agreement was signed in Paris by a Russian delegation led by Mr
Alexander Shokhin, the deputy prime minister, and the so-called Paris Club
of official creditors. It effectively reschedules over 10 years more than
Dollars 15bn of the total Dollars 20bn in capital and interest due this year
on Russia's foreign debt.
In Washington, the International Monetary fund said it was working on a new
temporary financing facility to help Russia and other former Soviet
republics 'facing particularly disruptive systemic shocks' in their
transition to market economies.
This is the IMF's contribution to the debate on how to get money to Russia
with less stringent conditions than usual for an IMF standby agreement. The
finance would be part of an international aid package which the Group of
Seven leading industrial nations is working on.
But officials said the facility - which might provide more than Dollars 2bn
to Russia - was only one of several options being considered by the G7. The
way is also now clear for commercial banks, grouped in the London Club, to
negotiate a similar rescheduling of private Russian debt servicing
obligations later this year.
Mr Yeltsin will be flanked at today's summit by Mr Shokhin and Mr Boris
Fyodorov, the finance minister who is involved in a fierce domestic struggle
for mastery over monetary policy with Mr Viktor Geraschenko, the chairman of
the central bank.
Mr Clinton is expected to mark his first summit by emphasising US desire to
offer practical support but limiting the hard currency on offer to the
Dollars 1bn or so which can be found from the existing US budget.
The US is keen to target Russia's fledgling private sector for special
attention while underlining the US commitment to a broader aid effort from
the G7 countries, including Japan which is hosting this year's G7 summit in
Tokyo this summer.
Japanese diplomats say Tokyo will increase its contribution to a G7 aid
package, despite a continuing dispute with Russia over the future of the
Kurile islands which has limited Japanese involvement to date.
Estimates of Russia's total foreign debt range from Dollars 80bn to Dollars
87bn, of which Dollars 38bn is owed to official creditors and another
Dollars 20bn to commercial banks. The rest mainly comprises unsecured trade
and other credits.
Page 3
Clinton tries to lead out the cavalry
