<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / The Lex Column: Invesco MIM
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Charles Brady is striving to clean up Invesco MIM. Yesterday's full-year
figures bear the scars. The cash settlement with Drayton Consolidated, costs
relating to IMRO's compliance investigation and the aborted plan to spin off
the US operations are reminders of a chequered past. The write-off of
development costs relating to Taurus, the Stock Exchange's now defunct
settlement system, adds insult to this list of self-inflicted injuries. A
possible fine by IMRO and the writ from Mirror Group pensioners have still
to be resolved.
In that context, Mr Brady's decision to assume the role of executive
chairman rather than introduce new blood seems strange. True, three new
regional boards each with a chief executive should contribute to a balance
of power. But Invesco must distance itself from the past if it is to stand a
fighting chance of turning the tide in UK fund management. Funds under
management rose slightly in Europe last year, but only after investment
gains. The investment performance may be improving, but institutions are
evidently reluctant to put their faith in the accident-prone group.
With 80 per cent of profits flowing from the US, the attitude of London
matters less than in the past. Invesco MIM's alliance with Peregrine of Hong
Kong adds promise to its prospects in Asia. On that basis, the shares might
look cheap despite the reduced dividend. With a long record of misadventures
to consider, though, the market is right to price in some risk.
</TEXT>
