<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / The Lex Column: MB-Caradon
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The sale of MB-Caradon's 25.3 per cent stake in CarnaudMetalbox has ended
one stock market guessing game but started another about what it will do
with the proceeds. MB-Caradon was always the more likely partner to sell out
of the Franco-British packaging group, given its primary interests in
building materials. By contrast, the French partner, CGIP, lives by managing
such investments. It was quite happy to increase its holding by another 7
per cent, giving it 46 per cent of the voting rights and ending lingering
bid speculation surrounding CarnaudMetalbox.
MB-Caradon sold its holding at a 12 per cent discount to its notional market
value. But that is normal for such a big placing. Besides, the price tag of
Pounds 473m would have been beyond the company's wildest dreams two years
ago. There was also the risk that a franc devaluation would have eroded its
worth.
The company seems inclined to sink the cash in the UK building materials
sector. MB-Caradon could easily gear up for a Pounds 1bn acquisition or put
together a string of smaller deals. But given the management's reputation
for caution and fixation with branded products, there is no obvious
candidate in sight. Other European economies are at different stages of the
economic cycle and MB-Caradon may find a suitable target overseas, should
nothing suitable emerge in the UK. It is a nice enough problem to worry
about. MB-Caradon's results on Monday are likely to suggest it has few
others.
</TEXT>
