<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Gains reversed in an erratic session
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DIFFICULT and confusing session, distorted by heavy falls in Wellcome and
in BAT Industries, saw the UK stock market gyrate through a range of more
than 33 points on the Footsie scale before closing 8.5 down on the day. In
addition to the setback to prospects for Retrovir, Wellcome's HIV treatment
product, and to BAT's sales outlook following a statement from Philip Morris
of the US, London traders had to cope with an erratic pound and weakness in
other European markets and on Wall Street - and all against the backcloth of
a UK rail strike which delayed commuters and reduced attendance in the City
of London.
In the event, around 4.6 per cent of market volume, and all of the net loss
in the Footsie, reflected heavy activity in BAT and in Wellcome. The rest of
the market was fairly quiet as it moved to the end of the first week of a
trading account extended to cover the Easter holiday weekend.
After opening cautiously, equities brushed off Wellcome's heavy fall, and
moved ahead as a strong futures market set the pace. The success of this
week's Pounds 3bn auction of government bonds continued to help gilts, which
soon put on three quarters of a point.
This encouraged the Bank of England to announce that a further Pounds 500m
of conventional gilts and Pounds 150m of index-linked would be available for
sale to the market on April 5. Bonds held up well, long dates closing more
than  1/2 up and index-linked around  1/4 better.
Confidence in equities was further boosted by Mr Norman Lamont, the UK
chancellor of the exchequer, who said there could be 'little doubt' that
over the past month, every economic indicator had pointed to recovery.
Better news on the housing market, and an opinion poll report of increased
economic optimism in the UK since the Budget of March 16, helped take the
Footsie ahead by 19.1 to 2,897.5.
But the market refused to challenge the Footsie 2,500 mark and trod water
until first reports from the Philip Morris meeting sent BAT plunging.
London was also perturbed that poor US jobs data might upset Wall Street.
The FT-SE Index continued to slide, showing a fall of 13.9 on the day just
before Wall Street opened with a loss of 30 Dow points.
The final ninety minutes of trading brought a modest rally, as the Dow also
steadied for a time from its initial setback. At its final reading of
2,869.9, the FT-SE was 8.5 down after a highly erratic trading day.
Seaq trading volume, although boosted by heavy selling of Wellcome and BAT
Industries, fell to 606.6m shares from Thursday's 678m.
</TEXT>
