<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / International Company News: Four European airlines set 1997
target for combined operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, Scandinavian Airlines System, Swissair and
Austrian Airlines are considering merging in four years to create Europe's
largest airline group.
Mr Leo van Weigk, one of the three board members of KLM, confirmed yesterday
that the four medium-sized European airlines were studying full integration
of their operations by 1997.
The four are seeking to create what they call a 'fourth force' in the
European airline industry to compete against the big three European carriers
 -British Airways, Air France and Lufthansa of Germany.
Although the four carriers are considering a full merger, this is likely to
take several years to complete because of the airlines' complicated
shareholding structures and problems over their respective international
landing rights.
The four carriers have set up 16 working parties to study various aspects of
co-operation leading eventually to a possible merger. Their conclusions are
expected to be put to the boards of the airlines in two weeks.
KLM said yesterday that the four boards were expected to reach a decision on
future co-operation and a possible merger next month.
Before any final proposal is decided it would have to be reviewed by the
European Commission, the shareholders and unions of the four airlines, as
well as by the north American anti-trust authorities.
This process could take a further six months, KLM suggested.
If successful, this could lead to closer collaboration between the four
airlines through a joint management group next year.
The joint operation could combine the sales, computer reservation systems
and fleet maintenance of the four airlines.
The concept at this stage would be to provide the benefits of a merger
without a full merger.
The combined operations of the four carriers would create one of Europe's
biggest airline groups, with a fleet of more than 270 aircraft carrying 30m
passengers a year and employing around 80,000 people.
</TEXT>
