<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Week in the Markets: Breath of fresh air for gold bulls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOLD market moved out of the doldrums this week, bringing excitement
back to the precious metals sector.
The rise began on Tuesday on trade buying in Europe. US funds pushed prices
higher, and the London bullion market broke through two important technical
barriers at Dollars 334 and Dollars 336 a troy ounce to finish at Dollars
336.15, a rise of Dollars 4.30 over Monday.
Such a bullish move spilled over into the silver and platinum markets.
Mr Nick Moore, analyst with Ord Minnett, part of the Westpac banking group,
pointed out that while volume had been thin, 'for a change producers did not
spoil the show by selling forward.' This was probably because the Australian
dollar price of gold had fallen, while the US dollar price was still
relatively low.
The rally continued full steam ahead early on Wednesday, taking the price
above Dollars 340 a troy ounce. But the market closed at Dollars 337.80, a
rise of only Dollars 1.70, leading to some suggestions that the rally would
be short-lived as the Australian dollar was weakening and the price was near
its peak in South African rand terms.
However, Mr Jeffrey Nichols, managing director of the American Precious
Metals Advisors consultancy organisation, suggested in his latest MetalsFax:
'In my view only a new wave of big sales can keep gold prices down.'
He was particularly encouraged by the recent interest of institutional and
substantial private investors in the gold share market.
'Retail (gold) investment activity in America and Europe - judging by demand
for bullion coins and small bars - is showing renewed signs of life,' he
said.
On Thursday the entire precious metals market eased on light profit-taking.
But all the charts - described by one observer as 'orgasmic' in technical
terms - were indicating a breakthrough into a higher range.
Yesterday the London bullion market was once again on the upward trail, with
a morning fix of Dollars 339.40 and an afternoon fix at Dollars 340.10 - the
highest level since October last year.
News that Singapore had imported a record 414 tonnes of gold last year
compared with 270 tonnes in 1991 added fuel to the flames, confirming the
strength of demand in the Far East.
Gold closed after a busy day at Dollars 339.75 a troy ounce, ahead Dollars
7.30 on the week, and dealers expect it to move into a new range above
Dollars 340 a troy ounce next week.
Silver closed at 394.50 cents a troy ounce, up 22.50 on the week, and
appears poised to move above 400 cents. Platinum closed at Dollars 365.50 a
troy ounce, up Dollars 9.90 on the week.
In contrast with the precious metals markets base metal prices on the London
Metal Exchange have had a quiet week. The rise in warehouse stocks has
continued relentlessly, and is likely to dampen any bullish sentiment.
Copper stocks are up a total of 7,425 tonnes this week to 362,125 tonnes,
the highest level for nine years. Cash copper shows a fall of Pounds 31 to
Pounds 1,411 a tonne. But the important three-month dollar figure has been
stuck below overhead resistance at Dollars 2,170 a tonne.
The week's rise in aluminium stocks totals 11,025 tonnes, giving a fresh
record of 1,736,325 tonnes. The gloomy fundamentals in this market took the
three-month price below Dollars 1,150 a tonne on Tuesday to 14 1/2 -month
lows, and it ended the week at Dollars 1,147.25, down Dollars 16.25 on the
week.
Zinc stocks rose above 600,000 tonnes yesterday to a new record. Three-month
metal, which dipped below important psychological support at Dollars 1,000 a
tonne on Thursday, closed yesterday at Dollars 1,006.5, down Dollars 4.75 on
the week. If it falls below the contract low of Dollars 987 a tonne, some
analysts believe it will rapidly retreat to Dollars 950. Stocks are likely
to increase further, and recent production cuts have been nowhere near
enough to boost prices.
Production cuts by the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries have
failed to meet their target of 23.58m barrels a day by 700,000 b/d,
estimates showed on Thursday. However, the figures were good enough to lift
Brent crude prices out of their recent narrow range and above Dollars 19 on
London's International Petroleum Exchange.
In late trading yesterday the Brent June contract was holding above Dollars
19, although the opening of Nymex knocked the market back.
The big news in the softs market this week was the collapse on Wednesday of
talks on renewing the international coffee pact with economic clauses. The
news arrived just after the London robusta market had closed, but in New
York arabica prices closed around 2 cents a lb higher.
On Thursday morning the London market moved sharply ahead on short-covering
on the back of the New York close, but was unable to sustain the rally.
Consumer stocks are high, and the peak roasting season has finished.
The July contract closed yesterday at Dollars 839 a tonne, down Dollars 17
on the week and Dollars 26 since the start of the talks a fortnight ago.
The markets have not expected the International Coffee Organisation
negotiations over the past 12 months to produce anything positive. But
nonetheless, each time an ICO meeting has ended in deadlock prices have been
adversely affected.
'The talks have been a deterrrent to trading,' said one London dealer,
welcoming the collapse. 'A cloud of uncertainty has lifted.'
