<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / UK Company News: Warnford agrees to amend accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WARNFORD INVESTMENTS, the property investment group, has agreed to amend the
treatment of properties in its accounts following discussions with the
Financial Reporting Review Panel, the watchdog of accounting standards.
The company had not complied with SSAP 19, the accounting standard which
requires investment properties to be shown at open market value, in its
accounts for 1991.
This shows that the Review Panel is determined to take action against
companies even when any divergence from accounting standards is clearly
flagged in the accounts.
Warnford had highlighted that its company balance sheet did not comply with
SSAP 19 in its fixed assets note in the accounts. The fact was also noted in
the auditor's report.
But Mr Sydney Treadgold, secretary to the Review Panel, said: 'It is not
enough just to have a qualified audit report or to disclose in the notes.
You have to comply with the provisions of the Companies Act.'
Mr Frank Martyn, finance director of Warnford, said the company had not
complied with SSAP 19 because to do so would have disclosed the open market
value of a property which the company was in negotiations to sell.
He said because the company only held one freehold property, its value would
have been clearly identifiable if it had complied with SSAP 19. But he
stressed that it was shown at market value in the consolidated group
accounts, so non-compliance had no effect on the group's value or earnings.
'It made no difference whatsoever to the market's perception of the
company.'
Mr Treadgold said: 'Reasons of commercial confidentiality can never really
be justification for departing from accounting standards.'
Warnford's directors have agreed to follow SSAP 19 in the future. But they
have managed to escape revealing the value of the property by re-allocating
it to a subsidiary. Mr Martyn said the property had still not been sold.
</TEXT>
