<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / UK Company News: Storm directors depart over dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STORM GROUP, the USM-quoted animation, licensing and merchandising company,
lost its chief executive and a US-based executive vice president yesterday
after a boardroom disagreement over the future direction of the company.
Mr James Driscoll, chairman, founder and creator of The Shoe People, one of
Storm's childrens' cartoons, said they had disagreed with the decision to
refocus the group on its core royalty-driven licensing, merchandising and
publications activit-ies.
Although Storm will continue to develop animation ideas and undertake
commissioned cartoon productions, Mr Driscoll said it would no longer use
its own funds to make animated cartoons.
He said Mr Gary Smith, chief executive, and Mr Brian Larcher, executive vice
president of the US subsidiary, disagreed and resigned amicably. Last year
Storm spent between Pounds 1.5m and Pounds 1.7m on productions.
Meanwhile Mr Jerry Alpert, another US-based executive vice president of the
group, has been appointed to the board. Mr Alpert has been responsible for
building up the group's worldwide network of agents and developing its US
licensing business.
Mr Driscoll said yesterday that the group would announce two more large
worldwide licensing deals with 'major US properties' in the next two weeks.
Last year Storm was appointed Paramount Pictures' exclusive licensing and
merchandising representative in Britain. Paramount's properties include Star
Trek, Cheers and the Addams Family.
</TEXT>
