FT  03 APR 93 / UK Company News: Invesco shuffles board as profits fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESCO MIM, the UK-based fund management group, is to combine the roles of
chairman and chief executive into a single role, that of executive chairman.
That post will be filled by the current chief executive Mr Charles Brady.
The move is part of a wide-ranging reorganisation of the group's board
structure following a series of well publicised and highly embarrassing
business dealings under Invesco's former chairman and chief executive, Lord
Stevens.
Invesco will establish separate boards for each of its businesses in North
America, Europe and Asia and the group board will be restructured to include
a majority of non-executive directors. 'We hope to avoid what went on in the
past,' Mr Brady said in explaining why he had sought the new structure.
'There is a different regulatory culture in each of the three regions and we
must be sensitive to each.'
Mr Brady will be the only executive to sit on all three regional boards as
well as on the main board. He said that although the best practice in
corporate governance discourages combining the roles of chairman and chief
executive, he believed that the new board structure would ensure that
authority was not concentrated in a single individual.
Mr Brady also said the US Attorney's Office in Atlanta had dropped its
investigation into allegations that officials in the group's US division had
made gifts to officials at one of its big pension fund clients, the utility
company Southern Corporation. Mr Brady said Invesco had been asked to answer
questions last autumn by the US Attorney about the matter and that it had
since been told that the US Attorney was satisfied.
Yesterday, Invesco also unveiled its 1992 results, showing pre-tax profits
after exceptional items down from Pounds 14.5m to Pounds 12.6m. The dividend
for the year is being halved to 3p via a final of 2p. The results included a
Pounds 410,000 charge stemming from the write-off of systems and development
costs related to the Stock Exchange's decision to cancel its Taurus
paperless trading system. The company also took a further Pounds 2.8m charge
stemming from costs related to a feasibility study it conducted last year
into a flotation of the US businesses.
The company's results show that revenues from Invesco's US operations dwarf
those from Europe, where the company is losing institutional clients, and
Asia.
