<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / The news isn't all bad: New faces at the top of ITN indicate
that the news service is emerging from a difficult period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If Independent Television News were a manufacturer of dustbins, bicycles or
tomato ketchup rather than an award-winning British news organisation, there
is little doubt that the receivers would have been summoned two years ago.
Its costs were clearly out of control. Some industry observers even talked
of a 'black hole' in the accounts as losses mounted. There were unfortunate
diversifications into computers and property. And ITN's shareholders found
it almost impossible to agree on what action to take to arrest the slide.
Although the survival of the company was not in doubt, and the quality of
its journalism did not suffer, the company was forced into a difficult and
often painful restructuring from which it only now appears to be emerging.
On Monday, ITN's flagship programme, News At Ten, will be able to report:
The formal appointment of a new ITN chief executive, Mr David Gordon, chief
executive of The Economist magazine;
The completion of an ownership restructuring and the arrival of new
shareholders including Reuters and Carlton Communications, which took over
the London weekday franchise from Thames Television; The completion of a
news-supply contract with Channel 4, which adds to the five-year Pounds 268m
deal signed in December with ITV;
An outline of ITN's strategy as a profit-making business. Until recently,
ITN, a wholly-owned subsidiary of the ITV network, has provided a news
service without being expected to make a profit.
ITN's transition is best symbolised by the changing faces at the top of the
organisation. Sir David Nicholas, the supreme television journalist, handed
over his chief executive's role in 1991 to Mr Bob Phillis, who began the
process of cutting costs and making ITN more commercial. This task will now
be taken forward by Mr Gordon, who is both a former journalist and a
businessman. When he arrived at ITN, Mr Phillis - the new deputy
director-general of the BBC - inherited a Pounds 10m overspend. During his
two-year tenure he was forced to cut staff from 1,100 to 650.
'Bob Phillis has done an effective job in stabilising ITN and reducing
costs,' says Mr Leslie Hill, chairman of Central Independent Television and
an existing director of ITN who will also be a board member of the
restructured company.
The pressure for change was a direct result of the 1990 Broadcasting Act,
which required ITN to sell off 51 per cent of its shares to non-broadcasters
by the end of next year. The franchise round, when ITV licences were put out
to competitive tender in 1991, increased instability when three ITN
shareholders - Thames, TVS and Television - lost their franchises.
When their successors - Carlton, Meridian and Westcountry - took over, they
found that losses on the lease of ITN's London headquarters were running at
the rate of about Pounds 5m a year. The ITV companies had hoped to make a
profit by letting out unused floors in the Gray's Inn Road building.
Instead, with the collapse in the commercial property market, most remained
empty.
In response to this potential crisis, Mr Michael Green, chairman of Carlton
Communications who takes over as chairman of ITN, put together a four-member
consortium to take over the group - Carlton, Central, London Weekend
Television and Reuters. They were later joined by Granada, Anglia and
Scottish Television. Members of the consortium hope that the restructuring,
with the possible addition of a US network as a minority shareholder, will
be enough to make the government waive the 51 per cent requirement. The
consortium not only made a commitment of Pounds 30m to fund ITN but also
organised a Pounds 74m buy-out of the building.
But can ITN be turned into a wholly commercial business without compromising
editorial standards?
'Absolutely,' says Mr Gordon who is interested in exploiting international
opportunities. 'The exact form that this will take and with which partners,
is something that will be preoccupying me over the next few months,' he
adds. A link with a US network is possible.
The move to profit has already started. In the 17 months to the end of 1992
it is believed ITN made an operational profit of between Pounds 7m and
Pounds 10m, compared with Pounds 3m for the 12 months of 1991.
The improvement is expected to continue. In addition to the ITV and the
Channel 4 contracts, Mr Gordon is keen to expand ITN's video sales operation
and its programming activities, which include making news documentaries for
ITV. He also believes that rapidly changing technology should allow further
savings. 'ITN has further to go along the Bob Phillis road of reducing costs
and increasing efficiency,' says Mr Gordon.
'The whole point is to be able to put the money on the screen and hire
first-rate reporters and editors to convert pictures into programmes.'
The evidence so far is that cost-cutting has not reduced the quality of
ITN's news operation - although the November revamp of News at Ten -
featuring a brash blue set, heavy use of graphics and Trevor MacDonald as
the single anchorman - has led to accusations of a plunge down market.
ITN's editor-in-chief, Mr Stewart Purvis, produces counter-evidence. The
demographic profile of the viewership, he points out, has held steady. In
November 1990, 41 per cent of the News at Ten audience came from
professional and managerial groups; the percentage last February remained at
41 per cent.
News at Ten's share of the main evening audience during 1992 averaged just
under 52 per cent, and climbed to 53 per cent in the first quarter of 1993,
a nightly average of 7.1m viewers. Channel Four news has averaged more than
1m over the same period.
In terms of quality, an ITN reporter last week picked up the news
organisation's 10th British Academy award since 1980 for her coverage of
Serbian prison camps.
As Mr Purvis put it recently: 'Yes, we've cut costs; yes, we want more
people to watch our programmes; but, no, we haven't cut the quality of our
coverage.'
And finally . . . Mr Hill of Central has a clear idea of what he wants from
ITN. Apart from a return on his investment, he says: 'I favour trying to use
ITN's strength to be news supplier to the world.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
