<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Letter: Not so certain an impact on competitive tendering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JOHN H HALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, You concluded ('Court blow to contracting-out', March 25) that the
recent decision that the Transfer of Undertakings Regulations apply to the
contracting-out of prison education services is likely to have a major
impact on the rest of the government's market testing and competitive
tendering programme.
Of course every case can be distinguished on its particular facts, but the
nature of the transfer from the Home Office prison education service to
South Manchester College, two separate parts of the public sector, is very
much within the scope of the transfer regulations even within the terms of
the government's guidance.
It is easy to read too much from the European Court judgment in Rask, which
you cite. This turned on the specific facts that the incoming contractor had
bound himself to employ the same staff on the same terms and conditions,
thus effectively making the regulations apply. It by no means implies that
all cases of contracting out will be similarly decided; indeed, I would be
surprised if this transpires.
Our member companies are continuing to defend cases brought under the
regulations. In general, UK industrial tribunals are continuing to rule that
in simple contracting-out cases, where there is no agreement to transfer
staff, premises or equipment, and where the contractor reorganises the
service, Tupe does not apply.
John H Hall,
director general,
Cleaning and Support Services Association,
64 Southwark Street,
London SE1
</TEXT>
