<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Letter: Complexities that endanger financial regulatory
structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr CHRISTOPHER WILLMOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Re 'Study of finance regulators urged' (March 26), Taurus toppled
because, among other things, of the weight of sheer complexity; now the
financial regulatory organisations are in danger of suffering the same fate.
The organisations were established with the ultimate and simple objective of
protecting clients. In the wake of recent scandals, their role of protection
is expanding into the diverse requirements of compliance. This has resulted
in their proactive role in management functions.
The rationale for regulation is clear, but the process is having a
debilitating effect on the management of financial companies. The worry is
that the regulatory structure will collapse under the complexity of
compliance, leaving not only a regulatory vacuum but also an industry that
has lost its competitive edge.
Christopher Willmott,
58 Sutherland Square,
Kennington, London SE17 3EL
</TEXT>
