<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / No such thing as a free flight: Guy de Jonquieres and
Michael Skapinker examine what lessons the flawed Hoover offer holds for
other consumer businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES and MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hoover's free flights fiasco, which culminated this week in the dismissal of
three top managers and a Dollars 30m provision by Maytag, its US parent, may
have turned the company into a national laughing-stock. But for many other
consumer businesses, the affair has struck too sensitive a nerve to allow
much gloating.
Though Hoover's programme was deeply flawed, it is a stark reminder that all
sales incentive schemes involve risks - and that when things go wrong, the
consequences can be as severe for companies as for their customers. 'My
attitude is one of sympathy,' said one travel industry executive. 'There but
for the grace of God go all of us.'
Tempting buyers with promises of something for nothing is one of marketing's
oldest wheezes. Recently, recession and keener competition have brought many
new players into the game and provided a bonanza for consultants in
'value-added' or promotional marketing.
'There are loads of different rewards on offer - from free holidays to
compact discs and video-recorders,' says Ms Sue Short of the Institute of
Sales Promotion, an industry body. 'Many retailers launched programmes after
they saw Hoover's success in generating sales.'
Long popular with the tabloid press, 'value-added' promotions have spread to
quality newspapers, including the FT, with its promotions of 'Lunch for a
Fiver' and two business class air tickets for the price of one. Supermarkets
including J Sainsbury, Tesco and Safeway have all recently offered
incentives such as cheap air tickets and holidays and free computers for
schools.
About 140 groups have contracts with Air Miles, a company set up in late
1988, which give their customers credits towards the cost of air tickets. An
estimated 15 per cent of British households now collect Air Miles.
Foreign travel incentives are particularly popular, partly because excess
capacity in the travel industry makes them cheap to offer. Many airlines and
tour operators provide discounts for 'value-added' promotions free of charge
in exchange for the advertising they generate  - and also because they stand
to make profits by selling extras such as car rental.
Most such schemes have run smoothly, because experience has taught their
sponsors to take precautions against pitfalls. What distinguishes the Hoover
case is that the company seemed oblivious to the dangers. Indeed, in the
view of many marketing experts, it made almost every mistake in the book.
The key to 'value-added' schemes lies in calculating how many consumers will
take advantage of them. 'It is essential to know the full extent of your
exposure in advance,' says Mr Terry Leahy, marketing director of Tesco,
which rewards customers spending more than Pounds 25 at its stores by
contributing towards the cost of computers in their children's schools.
Many companies use sophisticated computer models to forecast the likely
take-up rate by eligible applicants. For travel-related schemes this
averages 10 per cent or less. If the rate risks being much higher, most
companies will insure against losses. Dixons, the electrical retailer, says
it will only run promotional schemes if it is sure they will be profitable.
Hoover neither did its sums properly nor, it says, did it take out
insurance. The company's most serious error was to generate an uneconomic
take-up rate by offering too good a bargain: the chance to acquire air
tickets worth as much as Pounds 400 by buying an appliance for only Pounds
119. Many consumers bought Hoover products simply to qualify for free
flights.
No other company in recent times has made such a generous offer. But then
most say their promotions, unlike Hoover's, are not designed to induce
consumers to make purchases they had no intention of making; rather, the aim
is to persuade those who are already in the market to choose one brand over
others.
Mr Tony Bennett, marketing director of travel agents Thomas Cook, which
recently ran a promotion with the consumer electronics company Sony, says:
'You don't get people going into Currys or Dixons saying they want a Sony
television; they say they want a television. All we want to do is influence
them at the point of sale to buy a Sony television.'
Outright free gifts, unless of trivial value, are also a rarity. Most
promotions require a further investment by consumers in order to take
advantage of an incentive. The most popular method is to offer discounts on
the total cost of purchases such as holidays, restaurant meals or air
tickets.
Some schemes are also designed to reward customer loyalty. Safeway recently
offered discounts of between 10 per cent and 15 per cent on Thomson
holidays, depending on how much customers spent on groceries over a
three-month period.
Hoover's problems were compounded by confusion about the conditions of its
promotion. This had already been amended at the insistence of the
Advertising Standards Authority, the industry watchdog, which objected that
it did not make clear that the free flights were limited to certain dates
and destinations. Yet thousands of consumers still claimed to have been
misled.
'Hoover were not bold enough about the restrictions on their programme. By
the time people came up against them, they were emotionally committed to
taking the flights,' says one travel manager. Worse still, many customers
who had complied with the conditions were kept waiting for flights by the
travel agents administering the scheme.
According to Mr Steve Dowdle, marketing director of the UK subsidiary of
Sony, avoiding customer complaints is the first rule of 'value-added'
promotions. 'We have turned down schemes which looked marvellous on paper
because the conditions were too complex,' he says. Sony also sets up a
telephone helpline for every special offer. 'If more than 1 per cent of
eligible customers complain, a promotion has not worked,' says Mr Dowdle.
Companies such as Sony, Sainsbury and Tesco are acutely aware that whenever
they launch a promotion, they put on the line their single most precious
asset - their brand. For them, a short-term sales boost is valueless if it
is achieved at the expense of customers' long-term confidence in them as
reputable suppliers.
But do special promotions really yield tangible benefits - or are they
simply necessary to match the competition? Tesco says market research shows
well-run schemes enhance customer loyalty. Mr Don Gray, marketing director
of Express Newspapers, says they can raise circulation by up to 5 per cent -
though he is unsure how much of such gains is permanent.
The FT says promotions help it both to forge a closer relationship with
readers and to build up information about them which is useful in selling
advertising.
Mr Dowdle of Sony is more sceptical, saying his company engages in special
offers mainly to satisfy retailers. 'I would love to do no promotions at
all, because I'd like to feel that people choose Sony because of its
products, not for the incentives,' he says.
Mr David Pugh, marketing manager of the Telegraph group, fears the Hoover
fiasco has devalued even reputable promotions. 'The next time we run a
special offer, questions will inevitably arise in readers' minds,' he says.
'We will have to go out of our way to distance ourselves from Hoover-type
schemes.'
Given that consumers' right to legal redress over poorly handled promotions
is often unclear, such prudence is probably their best guarantee against
future fiascos. But that is small consolation to Hoover as it struggles to
repair damage to its reputation which threatens to linger on long after the
financial costs of the affair have been settled.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
