<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Letter: A recipe for more stable small business financing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr LEON H LIEBMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your editorial, 'Bankers and small business' (March 1) reported the
view of Mr Brian Pearse, chief executive of Midland Bank, that 'the system
of financing small business should be fundamentally rethought'. I agree.
However, his prescription is flawed.
Neither tax breaks nor interest subsidies would have prevented the small
business lending disaster which UK banks experienced. Preventing its
recurrence rests in part with banks adopting three policies leading to more
conservative small company management.
First, all long-term lending should be as term loans with fixed amortisation
schedules providing for full repayment of the sum borrowed. This will reduce
the likelihood that the bank will find itself providing permanent capital in
the form of short-term debt.
Second, all overdrafts should require that the borrower not use the
overdraft for 90 consecutive days in each business year. This will help
guarantee that overdrafts are for seasonal purposes or infrequent
occurrences only.
Third, businesses should be required to increase their principal repayments
pound for pound with owners' increases in their personal compensation. This
will speed debt repayment, reduce balance sheet leverage and guarantee
earnings retention.
Without any other actions by banks these three steps will lead to stronger
smaller company balance sheets and will mandate more conservative company
management. That is what is required to survive a severe recession - not
government subsidies to banks.
British banks have a special advantage. Their first fixed and floating
charge stands ahead of all other claims. The result is they 'enjoy' the
benefit of a shift of liabilities to the Treasury when struggling companies
do not pay tax liabilities in response to banks' pressures to reduce loans
outstanding. That is subsidy enough.
Leon H Liebman,
2 Neville Terrace,
London SW7 3AT
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
