<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Leading Article: The lure of bonds
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Domestic investors were out in force at the Bank of England's Pounds 3bn
auction of 20-year gilt-edged stock on Wednesday. But so, too, were the
foreigners; and that suggests that there is at least one respect in which
the chancellor's Budget strategy has started to work. There is nothing that
bond investors and currency markets like more than the sound of a domestic
electorate wailing about tax increases and spending cuts.
Hence the stability of sterling over the past 10 days and the success of an
auction that was regarded by analysts as far from a foregone conclusion.
Having established a floor under sterling the authorities will now be hoping
that this was a mere down payment - the start of a great tidal flow of
foreign capital into gilts.
For those British investors who have been brought up to regard gilt-edged
stock as one of the more effective ways of blowing an inheritance, this is
all a little baffling. But in a global market there will always be investors
for whom someone else's government's bonds, however suspect to the native
eye, will appear more attractive than their own. This is particularly true
when viewed from the perspective of the world's biggest creditor country,
Japan.
While the Japanese equity market was suffering from a collapse as severe as
the Wall Street crash of 1929, yen bond prices were rising at an astonishing
rate. Investors who bought at the bottom in autumn 1990 had nearly doubled
their money by February of this year. But then the party came to an end,
just as the equity market started to recover.
With government bond yields back around the 4 1/4 -4 1/2 per cent range,
compared with just under 4 per cent a month ago, the case for investing in
British gilts at 8 1/2 per cent looks more compelling, especially for
insurance companies that are permitted to pay bonuses out of income, but not
out of capital.
Much the same argument applies elsewhere. With the US economy recovering,
the dollar weakening further against the yen and the post-election bond
market boomlet at an end, recession-hit Europe is the obvious place for the
Japanese to go. All they have to do is to convince themselves of the
credibility of a given currency parity, and the extra income over and above
the yield on Japanese bonds becomes attractive.
French bonds
An obvious case in point is France, now that the elections are out of the
way. It is clear that French real rates of interest are too high, because of
the commitment to the franc fort policy. It is also clear that D-Mark rates,
to which French rates are tied via the Exchange Rate Mechanism, will come
down in the course of the year, since output in the German economy has been
contracting sharply. If the French manage to stay within the ERM, short-term
interest rates will fall closer to German rates, reflecting a reduction in
the risk premium - the compensation required by the market for not being in
more stable D-Marks. And this in turn will exert a gravitational pull on
long bond rates, which now stand at around 7 1/4 per cent, compared with an
underlying inflation rate of around 2 per cent.
Increased credibility
Certainly the credibility of the franc appears to have increased over the
past month. Three month Euro franc interest rates have come down from 12 to
10 per cent since late February - far more than the comparable decline in
D-Mark rates from 8.25 to 7.88 per cent. So the risk premium is narrowing.
The new French government, meantime, is helping the process by tightening
fiscal policy and promising independence for the Bank of France by August.
But before jumping to the conclusion that the market in European integration
is making a comeback, it is important to recognise that international
investors can have short time horizons. Today they are impressed by the
anti-inflationary credentials of Mr Edouard Balladur, who heads the new
centre-right government. But if strains develop in Franco-German relations
and rising unemployment causes political ructions, the market will suddenly
remember that it was Mr Balladur, who as minister of finance in the incoming
Chirac government in 1986, responded to over-high real rates of interest by
prompting an immediate devaluation of the franc within the ERM.
Nor are the wider tensions within the ERM resolved. The Danish referendum in
May provides another hurdle for the system. With the peseta looking
vulnerable on fundamentals, a far bigger hurdle may be presented by the
Spanish elections in the autumn. The currency markets are still willing to
test the weaker members of the system. If the result is realignment, then
the franc could come back into the firing line.
For the British government, the currency markets are no longer such a
daunting obstacle. But with a Pounds 50bn public sector borrowing
requirement, their verdict remains important because it holds the key to
future funding. The authorities will be put to the test monthly, in each new
gilt auction. It may not always be so comfortable.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    FRZ  France, EC.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
    DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
