<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / The going gets tough for Asian finance: The Bank of
England's dispute with Albaraka has raised the spectre of BCCI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHEIKH Saleh Abudallah Kamel is remarkably phlegmatic for a man who has had
to start repaying Pounds 83m in deposits to 10,000 depositors after an
unresolved dispute with the Bank of England. 'The Bank was very tough, and I
am glad about that,' he says. 'They should be tough with banks.'
But the enforced suspension of his Albaraka International Bank's
deposit-taking activities has raised questions about whether the Bank is
being too tough with lending to Asian businesses in the wake of the closure
of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International nearly two years ago.
The Albaraka situation is the latest in a series of incidents involving
banks with links to Britain's Asian community. The putting into
administration of the Equatorial Bank last month followed the winding up of
the Mount Banking Corporation on the Bank's initiative in October.
Mr Keith Vaz, Labour MP for Leicester East, has called for a parliamentary
inquiry into the Bank of England's treatment of banks' lending to Asian
businesses. He says it seems 'more than a coincidence' that the Bank has
been so strict.
The Albaraka case carries echoes of BCCI. The Bank of England appears to
have believed that the Albaraka's true 'mind and management' were in Saudi
Arabia although it does not operate as a bank there.
The Bank seems to have feared another case of a bank not supervised
adequately in any country although operating in several. As a result of
BCCI, international central bank supervisors insist on banks being
supervised on a consolidated basis in a 'home' country, the judgment of
which other countries can rely on. The Bank insisted yesterday it had no
argument with banks operating according to Islamic Sharia principles. In
Albaraka's case this means not dealing in pork products or armaments. The
bank also does not pay or charge interest on deposits or loans.
Islamic principles are not bad for profits. Sheikh Kamel says Albaraka could
not persuade Islamic banks elsewhere in the world to dilute his shareholding
 -and so take a stake in Albaraka - because they make 100 per cent returns
on equity compared with returns of below 10 per cent among most British
banks.
However, Albaraka and the Bank remain divided on whether it would be good
for Albaraka to have a broader-based ownership structure. The Bank seems to
have thought that this might dilute the control of Albaraka from Jeddah, and
turn it into a truly British bank which could be properly supervised.
Sheikh Kamel says he will try to offer a different form of ownership to the
Bank by June. But he believes his sole ownership has been good for
depositors because he feels a sense of responsibility towards them. Last
year he injected Pounds 15m of capital.
'I am responsible for every penny if I am the only owner. If there are a
thousand owners, how can any of them be truly responsible?' he says. The
Sheikh also argues that the Basle principles for consolidated supervision
are wrong, and that his group's 22 banks should operate independently.
Sheikh Kamel says the effort to have the holding company's banks supervised
from a single country, leaving the Bank to rely on foreign supervision as a
'host' country, is misguided. 'The Saudi authorities cannot control my acts
in London. That is what happened in the case of BCCI,' he says.
Bank of England officials believe the cases of Mount and Equatorial are
wholly different, although they also operated across borders, and lent to
British Asians. Both banks were affected by provisions against bad loans,
which eventually led to a loss of confidence and the withdrawal of deposits.
The fortunes of such banks have partly been affected by the closure of BCCI
and a loss of confidence in smaller banks.
The Bank last week disclosed that it had launched a series of financial
'lifeboats' in the second half of 1991 to support a number of small and
medium-sized financial institutions.
Whether the Bank could have performed a different role in the Mount and
Equatorial closures may thus be irrelevant to the main problem: that the
BCCI closure has had a damaging effect on Asian finance. The emergence of a
public dispute over Albaraka is only a symptom of this difficulty.
</TEXT>
