<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Business may win postal discounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE BUSINESS users may be given greater scope to secure discounts from the
Post Office through sorting their own letters and delivering them in bulk to
designated collection points, Mr Edward Leigh, junior trade and industry
minister, told the Commons yesterday, Ivor Owen writes.
While ruling out complete deregulation of letter deliveries, he indicated
that the wider use of 'downstream access' to introduce greater competition
was among the options being considered.
Insisting that full de-regulation would not be appropriate, Mr Leigh said
'some routes would be inherently unprofitable, and a free market would not
provide them at an affordable price'.
Mr Leigh reaffirmed that it was intended to maintain a universal postal
service with a uniform tariff so as not to disadvantage less accessible
areas. On the privatisation of Parcelforce, the Post Office's parcels
division, he said the government was still considering the timing and the
most appropriate method.
