<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Goldcrest man faces charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Quested, chief executive of film company Goldcrest, has been
arrested and charged with conspiring to falsify accounts in connection with
the Serious Fraud Office inquiry into Brent Walker, the property and leisure
group.
In a further widening of the prosecution more fraud charges were also
brought yesterday against Mr George Walker, the former Brent Walker
chairman, and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, the company's former finance director.
Mr Quested, who headed Goldcrest when the film company was a Brent Walker
subsidiary, was charged with one count of conspiring with Mr Walker, Mr
Aquilina and Mr Donald Anderson, a former Goldcrest finance director, to
falsify accounting documents by over-stating profits and assets between 1984
and 1987.
Mr Walker and Mr Aquilina were charged with the same offence when they
appeared at Bow Street magistrates court yesterday. Mr Walker already faces
four charges of theft of Pounds 12.5m and false accounting, and Mr Aquilina
two counts of false accounting. The three men were remanded on bail until
April 28. A warrant has been issued for the arrest of Mr Anderson whose
whereabouts are unknown.
Mr Quested took charge of Goldcrest, the British company which made
Oscar-winning films such as Chariots of Fire, in September 1987. His
appointment heralded a move downmarket in the output of the company.
Mr Quested also worked with Mr Walker when both were fellow directors of
Trilion, a USM-quoted television production company. Both resigned from the
board in February 1990. Goldcrest was sold off by Brent Walker in October
1990 with Mr Quested remaining as chief executive.
Banks led by the TSB yesterday resumed their High Court bid to have Mr
Walker declared bankrupt. They are claiming Mr Walker has breached his
obligations under the voluntary arrangement reached with creditors in
September to repay debts of over Pounds 150m. The hearing will continue next
week.
</TEXT>
