<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Anger increases over Royal Navy job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT came under renewed attack yesterday over its announcement
that the Royal Navy would be cut by an extra 5,000 jobs to 50,000 by the
late 1990s.
The government will face questioning from MPs about the cuts later this
month.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, the Tory chairman of the Commons defence committee,
said he had not been expecting further cuts.
He told BBC radio: 'My committee is looking at the Royal Navy in an inquiry
at the end of this month. This will give us a great deal extra to explore.'
The committee is scheduled to take evidence from Ministry of Defence
officials on April 28, and arguments over the new reductions might lead it
to question ministers as well.
Opposition MPs have already accused the Ministry of Defence of following
Treasury orders when planning further cuts, rather than considering defence
priorities.
Some MPs were angered over the way the ministry had not made the cutback
announcement through a parliamentary statement, which would have allowed
ministers to be challenged. The news was issued instead through the
ministry's press office on Thursday.
The ministry insisted that there was no need for a formal statement because
the figure was an assessment rather than a final judgment.
The extra reduction in the Navy is the first clear indication of government
plans for further defence cuts beyond the timespan of the cuts outlined in
its Options for Change review - due to be completed in 1995.
The reduction reflects increasing pressure on the defence budget. It is also
an indication that armed forces chiefs are trying to maintain a full range
of military capabilities even if that means cutting service numbers.
The Royal Air Force is also expected to make further cuts. Under Options for
Change the defence ministry scheduled a cut from 89,000 to 75,000 between
1992 and 1995. Senior RAF officers say the pruning of support services is
now likely to leave a total of well under 70,000.
The Navy announcement has reinforced expectations that the defence ministry,
which has to find savings of Pounds 1.05bn over the next two financial
years, will make further cuts in both the surface and submarine fleets.
Defence officials say that the extra round of naval redundancies is not a
direct result of the government's change of mind about Army cuts.
However, when the government announced in February that it would restore
3,000 Army jobs and cancel two regimental mergers it made clear that the
cost would have to be met from other parts of the defence budget.
</TEXT>
