FT  03 APR 93 / Spain is accused in ferry row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN yesterday accused Spain of breaching European Community obligations
by seeking to prevent Cenargo International, a British shipping company,
from introducing a ferry service between southern Spain and Morocco, Ivor
Owen writes.
Mr Steven Norris, the junior transport minister, told the Commons the
company was entitled to operate a service between a member state and a third
country under the single European market.
He said the government was seeking to protect the legitimate interests of
Cenargo, which would incur substantial losses if the service could not start
later this month. 'It is the whole principle of the single market which is
at issue,' said Mr Norris.
He welcomed the decision of the European Commission to institute infraction
proceedings against Spain, but noted that the process would take 'a great
deal of time to complete'.
