FT  03 APR 93 / French trawler skipper arrested
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SKIPPER of the French trawler La Calypso, which abducted three Royal
Navy officers on Sunday, was under arrest last night.
Earlier his vessel had been boarded by officers from the fisheries
protection vessel HMS Jersey and escorted into St Peter Port, Guernsey, in
the Channel Islands.
The vessel was detained for failing to obey lawful commands on Sunday, when
three naval officers who had boarded it because of suspicions that it was
fishing illegally in British waters were held on board and taken to
Cherbourg, France.
La Calypso was boarded close to the British six-mile limit, the Ministry of
Agriculture said.
The French maritime authority in Cherbourg said La Calypso was 'totally at
fault' in sailing into British waters.
But a spokeswoman for the French fishermen of lower Normandy accused the
Royal Navy of 'severe provocation'.
France's new conservative government has moved swiftly to try to quell the
fishermen's protests.
Mr Alain Juppe, foreign minister, at a meeting in Paris with Mr Douglas
Hurd, his British counterpart, yesterday reiterated France's commitment to
maintain the existing Franco-British agreement on Channel Islands fishing.
Mr Edouard Balladur, the new French prime minister, announced that he would
meet fishermen's leaders on Tuesday.
Last weekend's clash followed weeks of violent protests from French
fishermen who want restraints on fish imports.
