<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Leyland Daf rescue suffers double blow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS to rescue Leyland Daf, the beleaguered UK truck and van maker,
suffered two serious setbacks yesterday.
One of the company's main components suppliers, Automotive Products,
announced that it had stopped delivering crucial components to the Leyland
Daf plants.
It also emerged that Iveco Ford Truck, Leyland Daf's main rival in the UK,
is seeking to persuade 11 of Leyland Daf's 52 main dealers to change
franchise.
Mr Murdoch McKillop and Mr John Talbot, the joint administrative receivers
for Leyland Daf, failed in the High Court yesterday to gain an order
compelling Automotive Products to continue supplying components, chiefly
brake assemblies and clutches, to the truck-assembly plant at Leyland,
Lancashire, and to the van plant in Birmingham.
The receivers warned that production could be halted at the van plant as
early as Monday and truck assembly could be stopped by late next week.
It is understood that as many as 15 components suppliers are refusing to
supply Leyland Daf, although the Automotive Products case is the most
critical.
Automotive Products, a subsidiary of the BBA group, is refusing to deliver
more brake and clutch components until it is paid more than Pounds 758,000
that it says it is owed for parts supplied before Leyland Daf went into
receivership in February.
It would take Leyland Daf months to establish an alternative supplier.
Counsel for the receivers argued in the High Court that Automotive Products
was in breach of European Community trading law by abusing its dominant
position as a supplier and holding the company to ransom.
Sir Donald Nicholls, the vice-chancellor, ruled that 'it was not seriously
arguable' that Automotive Products' conduct infringed EC law. He said it
would be improper to express any view on the criticism of Automotive
Products' conduct.
The receivers are expected to take the case to the Court of Appeal early
next week.
It is understood that Leyland Daf owed unsecured trade creditors about
Pounds 82m when it collapsed into receivership.
Mr John White, BBA group managing director, said yesterday that the company
was continuing to negotiate with the receivers. 'We are still very happy to
supply if either we get paid or if we get our goods back.'
Mr White said that BBA had a 'retention to title' clause in its supply
contract with Leyland Daf. He added: 'I advised the receiver that I cannot
continue to supply unless I receive substantial monies due to me, or the
receiver recognises my right to recovery of the goods.'
Iveco Ford Truck, which narrowly lost the leadership of the UK truck market
to Leyland Daf in 1991 and 1992, announced that three of Leyland Daf's
leading dealers were joining the Iveco Ford franchise.
Mr Alan Fox, Iveco Ford managing director, said heads of agreement had been
signed with a further three dealers and negotiations were at an advanced
stage with five more.
</TEXT>
