FT  03 APR 93 / Nigeria pressed to end petrol subsidy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Nigerian government is under increasing pressure to begin phasing out
its petroleum price subsidy, Paul Adams reports from Lagos. In the past two
weeks, anticipation of the price rise has spurred the racketeering which
causes much of the domestic supply of 300,000 barrels a day to be smuggled
abroad. A tanker of fuel worth N40,000 at official prices can fetch N1.2m in
neighbouring Francophone states. Mr Philip Asiodu, the oil minister in the
transitional council, acknowledged to industry leaders yesterday that the
price rise was necessary to stop the chronic mismanagement of Nigeria's oil
assets.
