<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Paris tackles Gatt as urgent priority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE's new government yesterday announced that a re-appraisal of the Gatt
trade negotiations was its 'most urgent' economic priority, as its foreign
minister crossed swords with his UK counterpart on the issue.
At his first formal cabinet meeting, Mr Edouard Balladur, the prime
minister, asked his trade and farm ministers to draw up proposals to reflect
the new conservative government's unhappiness with the course which the
Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks have taken recently.
On Tuesday Mr Balladur will receive leaders of France's farmers, who are
against November's draft EC-US farm accord, as well as leaders of fishermen
who have separate grievances with Brussels about cheap fish imports.
After an otherwise harmonious meeting in Paris with Mr Douglas Hurd, the UK
foreign secretary, Mr Alain Juppe, France's foreign minister, said France
wanted 'the time to put the international trade dossier on a new footing'.
Recalling the previous French government's position, Mr Juppe complained of
lack of balance, in the November transatlantic farm deal and in the Gatt
negotiations, between concessions in agriculture and non-farm aspects of
trade.
Mr Hurd said it was 'perfectly natural' the new French government 'should
need a certain time to establish its position'. But he stressed Britain's
view that last November's farm deal, reducing the EC's subsidised farm
exports and oilseed output, was balanced.
'We don't want to see it unpicked on this side of the Atlantic, because
there are plenty of people on the other side of the Atlantic who want to
unpick it,' Mr Hurd said.
Mr Philippe Seguin, the conservative politician who led the 'No' campaign in
last autumn's Maastricht referendum, has been appointed president of the
National Assembly.
The appointment places Mr Seguin, 49, who was minister of social affairs in
a past conservative administration, in a powerful position. Mr Seguin,
together with Mr Charles Pasqua, now interior minister, have lobbied
forcefully within the Gaullist RPR against France's monetary links with
Germany and the franc fort policy of maintaining a strong currency.
</TEXT>
