<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Canberra aims for budget deficit cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Australian government yesterday foreshadowed a tightening of fiscal
policy to achieve its target of bringing the budget close to balance over
the next four years.
Mr John Dawkins, the federal treasurer, said there would be no 'precipitate'
attempt to eliminate the forecast deficit of ADollars 15.9bn (Pounds 7.50bn)
for the year to June, equivalent to 4 per cent of gross domestic product
(GDP).
But the federal budget in August would include specific measures intended to
reduce the deficit to 1 per cent of GDP by 1996/97.
'The government has shown in the past its willingness to adjust fiscal
policy as circumstances require. I can assure you that we will not flinch
from dealing with the emerging policy requirements.'
The treasurer's comments were underlined by Mr Ralph Willis, the finance
minister, who said the government would not rely entirely on economic growth
to reduce the deficit.
'I would think that we need to take some positive steps and not just rely on
the recovery  .. to reduce the deficit,' he said.
The ministers' comments contrast with reports official suggestions last week
that Mr Dawkins regarded the deficit as less important than a reduction in
unemployment from its near record level of 11.1 per cent.
Mr Bernie Fraser, the Reserve Bank governor, and Standard &amp; Poor's, the US
credit rating agency, have made it clear that a reduction in the deficit is
regarded as essential by the financial markets.
Mr Dawkins also announced a review of national savings and plans for
increased budgetary co-operation with state governments.
</TEXT>
