<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / The Clinton-Yeltsin Summit: Clinton tries to lead out the
cavalry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THERE have been 25 summits between the inhabitants of the White House and
the Kremlin in the 33 1/2 years since President Dwight Eisenhower
entertained Mr Nikita Khruschev at Camp David in September, 1959.
All of them, even President George Bush's valedictory trip to Moscow in
January to sign the Start Two treaty, were dominated by the arms control and
security issues that characterised the cold war. President Bill Clinton
meets President Boris Yeltsin of Russia in Vancouver today with a different
purpose in view.
In the words of a senior administration official, 'economics have now
replaced traditional security issues as the centrepiece of US-Russian
relations'.
'Past summits,' he went on, 'were designed to minimise the harm each could
do to the other. Now the intent is to maximise the good.'
Mr Clinton himself made an eloquent pitch for the new partnership in a
speech on Thursday aimed not only, in its call for 'a strategic alliance
with Russian reform', at Americans and Russians but also at other
industrialised nations. Implicit in it was the contention that, if past
summits had seen the US take on the role of protector of its allies,
Vancouver required that US leadership be followed by G7 action.
Fine words and Mr Clinton will be laying before Mr Yeltsin a series of
practical proposals to put flesh on the bones of this promised new
'partnership'. Conventional security considerations will be on the agenda,
since there is unfinished nuclear missile business and regional conflicts to
be addressed, but the US sees them as essentially secondary now.
Mr Clinton has a lot riding on his first presidential foreign foray.
There is little disagreement with his analysis that promoting the cause of a
co-operative market-oriented Russian democracy is of immeasurable benefit to
the US. Opinion polls demonstrate broad support for his approach, as did, in
a statement this week, the four living former Republican presidents.
His problems are twofold: first the US ability to determine the course of
events in Russia itself is minimal. It may support, with words and some
money, the reform process but it cannot ensure the survival of Mr Yeltsin,
the embodiment of that reform, nor of other reform-minded leaders. 'Only the
Russians can save Russian democracy' is the administration's invariable
litany.
Second, the president has his own money problem. Officials refuse to put
dollar figures on what the bilateral offer to Mr Yeltsin will be, but
concede that, initially, it will only be drawn from funds already approved
by Congress for Russia in the last and current fiscal year, plus a little
extra. Informed speculation suggests about a Dollars 400m total this year
and Dollars 700m next, though these estimates may be low.
This recognises the domestic political reality that there is not much of a
constituency, in Congress or the country at large, for throwing large sums
of money at Russia at a time when budget cutting at home is the order of the
day.
Within these limitations, however, the bilateral US programme is designed to
be eye-catching. Officials say that three quarters of its value will be
directed 'outside of Moscow' and to 'non-governmental partners.'
Its elements are likely to include a Dollars 200m-plus privatisation support
programme, an 'enterprise fund' for new business, starting small but
growing, housing construction projects for returning Russian military
officers and men, humanitarian asssistance in the form of food and
medicines, the dispatch of US technological and management experts,
additional grain credits, and assorted energy initiatives, including,
possibly, an oil barter arrangement.
But the bilateral proposals, according to senior officials, are also seen as
'a catalyst to multilateral action.' Vancouver, they say, is part of a
continuous process, the next stage of which is the meeting of the Group of
Seven's foreign and financial ministers in Tokyo on April 14. The US expects
other nations to have announced their own individual assistance programmes
by then and that the Tokyo session takes real decisions.
Elements of the international package known to be under consideration,
perhaps worth Dollars 30bn, include a Dollars 6bn rouble stabilisation fund,
as much as Dollars 9bn in loans from the IMF, World Bank and the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development, some Dollars 4bn in debt relief
this year, and a large assortment of trading credits.
A good portion of last year's Dollars 24bn package remains unspent and the
US accepts that today disbursement of more depends on Russia meeting
reasonable conditions, not least a responsible monetary policy.
Thus Mr Clinton will be pressing Mr Yeltsin for some firm commitments to
reform, to which, in Moscow's current political climate, the Russian
president may find hard to respond. The sense of US confidence is guarded.
But the alternative - sitting back and letting events in Russia take their
course - is not an option while Mr Yeltsin is in office, nor may it be for
as long as there is life in the Russianreform movement.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CAZ  Canada.
</CN>
