<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / President plunges into sell-off debate: Christopher Bobinski
and Anthony Robinson assess Poland's privatisation difficulties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI and ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Lech Walesa has re-emerged as a protagonist in the Polish
privatisation debate, raising the political stakes in the latest attempt by
the coalition government to gain parliamentary backing for its modified
mass-privatisation plan.
Changes were made to the government's long-delayed plan by Mr Janusz
Lewandowski, privatisation minister, after former communists and rebels from
the right-wing christian national party had rejected the government's
original bill on March 18.
The contested aspects of the original plan included the role of foreign
managers in the proposed investment funds which would handle the portfolios
of privatised companies, and a demand for the free distribution of funds to
pensioners and civil servants in lieu of higher salaries blocked in 1991.
The former communist SLD party also argued that the privatisation scheme
should be treated as an experiment and brought in step-by-step, after the
management skills of the foreign-managed investment funds set up by the
scheme had been tested.
The government has responded by proposing that the shares of the first 200
companies be placed in a separate fund to be distributed free to pensioners
and state employees. But the government decided not to give in to the
anti-foreign investment manager sentiments of right-wing opponents, which
include a handful of rebels from the National Christian Union (ZChN) who
voted against the government of which they are coalition members.
The liberal democratic congress, Mr Lewandowski's own party, has threatened
to leave the government if the revised plan fails to win a parliamentary
majority. This effectively turns today's expected parliamentary vote into
one of confidence in the government.
A government defeat could have led either to early elections, unwanted by
most parties, or a reshuffle of the government coalition led by Ms Hanna
Suchocka.
The potential for a period of political instability, triggered by the
privatisation issue, has been increased by President Lech Walesa's decision
to put forward his own privatisation proposal. He remains dogged by his 1991
pre-election pledge that privatisation would leave Poles 100m zlotys
(Dollars 10,000) richer.
The president re-entered the fray last week. He gave his blessing to a new
political movement, the so-called non-party forum for reform. This is linked
to the siec (network), which is based on 260 Solidarity organisations in the
country's big factories and is widely perceived as a political platform for
Mr Walesa himself.
The meeting which set up the forum at Zdzieszowice, a coke works near
Gorazdze, called on the government to drop a mass-privatisation programme
'which treats workers as objects'. In its place, the meeting suggested,
Poles should be granted low-interest investment vouchers worth up to 300m
zlotys. The vouchers could only be used to buy state property and would be
essentially loans which would have to be repaid within 20 years.
Mr Walesa told Mr Lewandowski that he saw the investment grant idea as
complementary to the mass-privatisation scheme.
But the privatisation ministry fears that launch of the alternative plan now
could erode the government's majority in the vote on the scheme.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>PLZ  Poland, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
