<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Italian unions stage four-hour strike against unemployment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S three main trade union federations yesterday staged a staggered,
four-hour general strike, calling on the government to act urgently against
rising unemployment.
The strike came as the lira fell for the second time this week below the
level of 1,000 to the D-Mark, before recovering to L998. The currency's
weakness reflected market anxieties over the deadlock in efforts by Italian
politicians to agree on a way to find a stronger government.
The strike, which mainly affected public sector services and the civil
service, was accompanied by a series of demonstrations in the main cities.
Scuffles broke out in Turin and Naples, but the violence was less than
during the last such strike in November.
This was the 11th general strike in 12 years but yesterday rain reduced the
number of protesters on the streets. The protest against unemployment, now
reaching nearly 11 per cent of the labour force, was overshadowed by the
government crisis and the plight of the lira. But union leaders insisted
yesterday that the workers were likely to be those most prejudiced by the
government's faltering and the currency's decline.
The ruling Christian Democrats, dominant partners in the four-party
coalition headed by Mr Giuliano Amato, have come out strongly against the
idea of 'an institutional solution' to the political crisis. This hinged on
suggestions by President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro that a non-partisan figure,
such as the leader of either the senate or the chamber of deputies, assume
the leadership of an interim government after the referendums due on April
18, with the specific task of supervising electoral reform.
The Christian Democrats have been put onto the defensive, both by the
defection this week of the reformist Mr Mario Segni, and by the news that
Palermo magistrates were investigating the veteran Christian Democrat
politician Mr Giulio Andreotti, for alleged links with the mafia. The party
fears an 'institutional' government would annul its traditional influence.
The Christian Democrats are also hostile to the other main proposition -
accepting into the government representatives of the former communists, the
Party of the Democratic Left (PDS). The latter, for its part, is saying it
will only join the government if it contains people wholly untainted by
corruption scandals.
</TEXT>
