<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Bonn to bar crews from Awacs before court ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN crews on reconnaissance aircraft above the Adriatic Sea will not be
able to participate in the enforcement of the no-fly zone over former
Yugoslavia, pending a ruling by the German federal constitutional court.
It will rule on an appeal yesterday by the liberal Free Democrat party
(FDP), junior partner in the German coalition government, against a cabinet
decision to let crews stay on board Awacs aircraft.
The court will meet on Monday to study the appeal but has not said when a
ruling can be expected.
In a special cabinet session, ministers of the Christian Democratic Union
(CDU) and its sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU), voted that
German crews on Awacs could take part in Nato missions implementing the
no-fly zone over Bosnia.
However, the decision was immediately challenged by the FDP, which is asking
the court to consider whether German crews' involvement in enforcing the
no-fly zone is constitutional.
The coalition members have been clashing over interpretation of the
constitution. The CDU/CSU says that article 24 allows German troops to fight
in a Nato context.
But the FDP, as well as the opposition Social Democrats (SPD), say the
constitution prevents German military involvement outside Nato territory.
The SDP yesterday also filed an appeal on the question to the constitutional
court.
Awacs aircraft are conducting surveillance above the Adriatic and would tell
Nato's other forces how the no-fly zone is being enforced. A third of Awacs
crews are German.
Pending a court ruling, these crews would be asked to leave the Awacs if
Nato were to implement the no-fly zone. They would, however, be allowed to
prepare the aircraft.
CDU officials said they were hoping the court would rule in favour of the
cabinet decision in a couple of days.
If the court does not rule in favour, though, the matter would have to be
referred to parliament.
So far, the opposition SPD has refused to vote for constitutional changes.
</TEXT>
