<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Bosnian Serbs in peace wrangle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, yesterday proposed direct
negotiations between the three warring factions in Bosnia as a way to break
the impasse in the Bosnian peace talks.
In a speech to the self-styled Bosnian Serb parliament in Bileca, called to
decide whether to accept the international mediators' peace plan, Mr
Karadzic poured scorn on the proposed map dividing Bosnia-Hercegovina into
10 semi-autonomous provinces.
The plan, drawn up by Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen, and already endorsed by
the Bosnian Moslems and Croats, would confine Serbs 'to live in islands
surrounded by enemies,' he said. 'Accepting the maps, just as they are now,
would amount to unprecedented ethnic cleansing.'
Yet it is the Serb forces, who currently occupy 70 per cent of Bosnian
territory, who have been accused by the international community of killing
or expelling hundreds of thousands of Moslems from their homes.
At the same time, Mr Karadzic did not minimise the probable consequences of
a negative vote by the Bosnian Serb parliament on the Vance-Owen plan. He
warned it was likely to lead to stepped up sanctions, arming the outgunned
Moslem forces or even foreign military intervention.
In a move to put pressure on the Serbs to sign the plan, the United Nations
Security Council on Wednesday approved a resolution allowing Nato war planes
to shoot down aircraft flouting a five-month-old ban on flights in Bosnian
airspace.
Nato permanent representatives agreed yesterday in Brussels to send US,
British, French and Dutch fighters to enforce the no-fly zone. Mr Manfred
Worner, the Nato secretary-general said the plans to send the aircraft would
be ready less than two weeks from now.
Mr Karadzic said the UN resolution would only increase opposition to the
peace plan. But he nevertheless warned the 69 deputies of the parliament not
to delude themselves that the international community would fail to carry
out its threats.
In an attempt to soften his hardline approach, the Bosnian Serb leader said
the map boundaries proposed by the mediators were 70-80 per cent acceptable.
Direct talks between the warring parties could reduce the disputed territory
to 10 per cent and it was not worth 'killing each other' over such a small
area.
Though there appears to be little prospect of the parliament endorsing the
map as it stands, deputies may accept a proposal by Mr Vitaly Churkin,
Russia's special envoy to the peace talks, who has suggested the Bosnian
Serbs sign the uncontested part of the map and negotiate the rest.
Mr Churkin's compromise proposal has reportedly been approved by Mr Slobodan
Milosevic, Serbia's president, and Mr Dobrica Cosic, president of the rump
Yugoslav federation, Russian sources said.
Meanwhile, Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, the Norwegian Foreign Minister,
announced in Oslo he had agreed to take over from Mr Vance as the UN peace
mediator on the former Yugoslavia, joining Lord Owen, the European
Community's representative.
</TEXT>
