<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / La Scala upset over top job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Italian cultural establishment, reeling from accusations of financial
mismanagement and alleged corruption, is set for a further blow with the
likely imposition of a special administrator at Milan's La Scala opera
house.
The threat follows the decision by a regional appeals court in the province
of Lombardy to accept a claim by an splinter union group that the July 1990
appointment of Mr Carlo Fontana, La Scala's new superintendant, to a
four-year term, was illegal.
The case is the latest round in a running battle between Milan's famous
theatre and various dissident workers, who have taken a variety of legal
steps against its management.
The latest twist comes at a particularly sensitive time for La Scala, and
for Italy's arts world in general. La Scala has suffered this season from
critical attacks on Luciano Pavarotti, the tenor whose first-night
performance in Verdi's opera Don Carlos was given a less than rapturous
reception by many in the sophisticated audience.
Subsequent performances went well but Pavarotti's relationship with the
opera house has grown more strained since his last-minute decision to pull
out of performances in I Pagliacci, which opened this week. Other leading
Italian opera houses have also been no strangers to financial or management
disputes lately.
