<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Clinton joins Thorp nuclear plant row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton has stepped into the controversy over the Pounds
2.8bn Thorp nuclear reprocessing plant at Sellafield in a move which could
further delay the start of its operations.
Mr Clinton has told seven congressmen he will raise the issue with the
British government after his administration has looked into ways of
combating nuclear proliferation.
In a letter to the president on February 23, just days before his first
meeting with Mr John Major, the congressmen warned Mr Clinton that plutonium
produced at Thorp would add to the world's stockpile and increase the risk
of the spread of nuclear weapons.
The congressmen, led by Mr Pete Stark of California, also wrote to Mr Major
before his visit, but have not yet had a reply. Their letter urged that 'a
decision by the UK against commissioning the Thorp plant would be a
significant contribution to efforts to stem the proliferation of nuclear
weapons'.
The questions about the reprocessing plant took Mr Major by surprise on his
US visit and he called for hurried briefings from London.
Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, said four days ago that
preventing the spread of nuclear weapons was one of the administration's top
concerns when considering foreign aid requests. Mr Christopher's comments
followed news that North Korea had flouted a United Nations deadline for
inspection of its nuclear facilities.
However, US administration officials cautioned that the Thorp plant was not
high on their list of priorities, and doubted that it would become a
significant bilateral issue between the US and the UK.
The UK government is embroiled in three separate inquiries into whether the
plant should begin operating. President Clinton's interest in the
destination of plutonium produced by Thorp will complicate the British
government's task and could worry Thorp's foreign customers.
In a reply to the congressmen, President Clinton said that once the US had
concluded its review, 'we will surely wish to consult with the British on
appropriate steps we could take together to combat nuclear proliferation'.
Downing Street declined to comment last night on the possibility of US
intervention in British nuclear policy.
British Nuclear Fuels, which has built Thorp, said 'plutonium which Thorp
will reclaim cannot be converted into weapons grade material without
substantial expertise and equipment'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
