FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: MIM buys exploration venture
stake for ADollars 43m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MIM, the Australian metals and coal producer, has acquired 30 per cent of
Mount Fort Constantine, a copper and gold mining exploration venture, for up
to ADollars 43m (USDollars 30m).
Mr Norman Fussell, managing director, said the company had bought the stake
from Hunter Resources, a small Australian mining group. The other 70 per
cent is owned by Western Mining, another leading Australian mining group.
The Mount Fort Constantine joint venture, which operates in north-west
Queensland, includes the highly-rated Ernest Henry copper-gold deposit,
which is subject to legal proceed-ings.
If Ernest Henry is ultimately included in the MIM deal, the purchase price
will be ADollars 43. If not, MIM will grant Hunter Resources a 2 per cent
gross royalty in mineral production as settlement.
Mr Fussell said MIM regards Ernest Henry as among Australia's most
prospective copper-gold areas.
