<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Syncordia in telecom service
deal with BP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATLANTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SYNCORDIA, British Telecom's 18-month-old Atlanta-based subsidiary for
telecommunications network outsourcing, has won a contract from British
Petroleum. The oil company becomes Syncordia's fifth customer.
Syncordia will manage BP's voice, data, video and messaging services among
five sites in the UK and Stavanger, Norway. BP and Syncordia are also
negotiating to include additional sites.
Although the five-year contract's total value was not disclosed, Syncordia
said its first year was worth Dollars 12m.
BP said it believed the outsourcing arrangement would bring 'significant
operating and financial benefits'.
Last year, Syncordia began working with BP Chemicals, a unit of BP, managing
its communications network among 11 sites in seven European countries.
Syncordia, although it has been off to a slow start, aims to capture a
significant slice of the fast growing market for network outsourcing -
whereby companies contract out the management of their telecommunications
systems to specialists.
Competition in the global network outsourcing market, estimated to grow to
Dollars 4bn to Dollars 6bn by the mid-1990s, is increasingly tough, with
companies such as AT&amp;T, MCI and Unisource jockeying for market share with
BT.
For BT, Syncordia is a key element in its strategy to expand internationally
and become the world's leading supplier of telecommunications services.
</TEXT>
