<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / UK Company News: Thames TV shares fall 33p on provision news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THAMES TELEVISION, the independent production company, yesterday announced
it was making provisions totalling between Pounds 35m and Pounds 42m on
property and on Reeves, its US production arm.
The provisions were considerably larger than the City expected and the
shares fell 33p to 188p following their relisting yesterday.
The shares had been suspended partly because of the pending announcement on
provisions and partly because of a report in the Financial Times that
Pearson, the publishing, banking and oil services group which owns the FT,
was in exploratory talks to buy Thorn EMI's near-60 per cent stake in
Thames.
Yesterday Thames confirmed that it had been informed by Thorn that it was in
talks with Pearson, but that they were at a preliminary stage.
The provisions will be taken as extraordinary items. The company said that
pre-tax profits for 1992 were expected to be about Pounds 45m in line with
City expectations. A formal results announcement is expected in three weeks.
As a result of the provisions, mainly flowing from revaluations of central
London property and the Reeves library of programmes, there will be an
attributable loss.
Thames admitted that the interim dividend paid in September was a technical
breach of the Companies Act because full interim accounts had not been
submitted at the time. It was considering how to address the problem.
Early action by Pearson is not expected and there may now be a pause to see
how the Thames share price settles down following yesterday's disclosure. If
Pearson does decide to bid for Thorn's holding it will have to make a
general offer for all the shares of Thames.
</TEXT>
