<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Luggage locker row goes to EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAANND SYSTEMS, a company based in Livingston near Edinburgh, has complained
to the European Commission about alleged predatory pricing by the French
company Mors in the battle for orders for left-luggage lockers in railway
stations.
Raannd has complained to the commission that Mors won a contract in December
to supply lockers at Waverley station in Edinburgh, and at Queens Street and
Central stations in Glasgow, by setting prices in a predatory manner. Raannd
had offered to supply 700 lockers for about Pounds 400,000, and says Mors
undercut this by 40 per cent.
It is also complaining that it was undercut by Mors last August on an order
from British Rail for 700 lockers at Waterloo International station in
London.
The complaint came to light as ScotRail, BR's Scottish division, confirmed
that automated luggage lockers installed by Mors at Edinburgh Waverley were
being adapted after it was found they would only accept French and Belgian
coins. The problem with the coins was triggering the lockers' alarm system.
Mors has about 75 per cent of the European locker market and Raannd alleges
that Mors has violated article 86 of the Treaty of Rome which covers abuse
of market power.
Raannd says the commission has begun an investigation of the matter.
The company is also 'in dialogue' with Mors over alleged infringements of
Raannd's patents on its lockers.
Dr Gordon Rankine, Raannd's managing director, said that after complaining
to Sir Bob Reid, chairman of BR, he was advised the procedures for the bid
had been implemented correctly.
Nobody at Mors was available for comment yesterday.
</TEXT>
