<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Survey of Spain (14): A whiff of corruption - The Filesa
Case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS not Italy. But it is starting to smell that way. Political corruption
has become a burning issue in Spain.
Later this month a Madrid judge is likely to ask parliament to lift the
immunity on a congressman and a senator who are allegedly linked to a
judicial investigation into illicit funding of the governing Socialist
party.
The judge's probe, known as the Filesa case after a Barcelona-based group of
consultancy companies that allegedly bankrolled the government's 1989
general electoral campaign, has an identifiable Italian whiff about it.
Tax inspectors working for Judge Mariano Barbero last month compiled a
report that itemised a list of payments, totalling Pta1bn (Dollars 8.4m),
that the Filesa group received from leading domestic banks and companies in
return for consultancy reports and also a list of subsequent payments that
the group made to the Socialist party to cover its electoral expenses.
The report is an explosive one because it alleges that Filesa, which was
controlled by Mr Carlos Navarro, a congressman and former treasurer of the
Socialist parliamentary party, and by Sen Jose Maria Sala, administrative
secretary of the Catalan Socialist party, never wrote the consultancy
reports that it was paid for.
Compounding the damage, the report claims that Filesa directly paid service
companies supplying the Socialist campaign headquarters and that in order to
disguise the payments it took receipts for them from a group of companies,
called 2020, which is controlled by Ms Aida Alvarez, a former national
co-ordinator of the Socialist party's finances.
The Filesa case is viewed by some as the mere tip of a corruption iceberg.
The 2020 group itself has been linked in press reports to large consultancy
payments made by Germany's Siemens group at the time it was negotiating the
contract to supply the Madrid-Seville high speed train. Other press reports
have suggested backhanders were common practice among suppliers to last
year's Universal Exposition in Seville and certain Seville officials are
already under judicial investigation for allegedly receiving bribes from
construction companies.
The corruption spotlight was first trained on Seville, the main Socialist
power base, in 1991 when Mr Alfonso Guerra, the city's leading Socialist
politician, was forced to resign as deputy prime minister after his younger
brother was accused of political scams at the government's local
headquarters. Mr Guerra, who remains deputy leader of the Socialist party,
is responsible for the party's electoral campaigns.
Corruption by no means appears to be exclusively a Socialist party vice. The
centre right opposition, the Partido Popular, PP, has been severely
embarrassed by real estate scandals involving the chief executive of the
regional government of Cantabria, north Spain, one of the party's fiefdoms,
and three years ago it had to sack its national treasurer who was accused of
organising illicit funding in a scandal not unlike the current Filesa
affair.
The governing Socialists are taking the flak now but the problem is general.
Spain, much like Italy, has not adequately worked out how to finance a
democratic process in which the parties run large bureaucracies and spend
heavily during a never-ending round of municipal, regional and general
elections.
Budget allocations to the parties cover only a fraction of their running
costs, party membership is low and dues are derisory, and there is no
mechanism for tax-deductible political donations, which are in any case
curtailed by law. So far, the parliamentary parties have failed to agree on
limiting their campaign expenses but all are expected to refer to the need
for such legislation in their manifestos for the general elections later
this year.
One hopeful feature in the Spanish scenario is that corruption, thanks to
the press and to individual judges, has come out into the open. The Partido
Popular, which believes that it has put its own house in order, is now
fuelling the debate, for it rightly believes that is a vote-getter.
Unlike Italy, corruption has almost certainly not permeated the entire
political system. This is not because Spaniards are more virtuous but
because democracy was reintroduced only in the late 1970s and political
parties have consequently been at the game for a shorter period. There is no
suggestion, so far, that political leaders in Spain are themselves corrupt.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9222 Legal Counsel and Prosecution.
    P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Legal issues.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 34
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-16942</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDBB7AHGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930402
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Survey of Spain (13): The state needs cash - The background
to privatisation moves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN they really want to be nasty, which is fairly frequently, Spain's trade
unionists accuse Mr Felipe Gonzalez's government of pursuing Thatcherite
policies. This a travesty of the truth. The decade of socialist rule in
Spain has rolled forward the frontiers of the state, rather than back.
Since Mr Gonzalez formed his first government late in 1982, taxation has
become punitive and public spending has increased ever year by an average
2.3 per cent over the growth of the GDP.
The government has purposefully walked down the welfare state road.
Milestones have included substantially increased spending on pensions, where
expenditure rose from Pta1,100bn (Dollars 9bn) in 1982 to Pta3,100bn in
1991, and on education, where it went up from 2.5 per cent of the GDP in
1982 to 3.3 per cent in 1991.
Nothing could be less Thatcherite than the government's policy towards the
trade unions. Legislation during Mr Gonzalez's first term of office
significantly increased the power of works committees, formed by shop
stewards, in companies and the government is currently sponsoring a strike
law in parliament that has been largely drafted by the unions and is
virulently opposed by employers.
Union hostility towards the government, which is real enough, is in part due
to a level of unemployment that has never fallen below 15 per cent during
the Socialist decade and has currently climbed back to the 20 per cent level
of 1982. It is also a consequence of the rising expectations of society
during the boom years of the late 1980s when the rich indubitably got a lot
richer.
But union pressure ensured that industrial wages rose steeply as well in the
fattened calf years. In terms of unit labour costs Spain is now considerably
less competitive than it was when Mr Gonzalez came to power.
While the Thatcherite epithet was wholly misplaced before, unions may have
some justification in using it against the government from now on. Barring
the unlikely possibility of a Socialist-Communist party pact after the
general elections later this year, Mr Gonzalez, on his own or in coalition
with the minority nationalist parties, will be forced to shed at least a few
of his social democrat clothes.
The drift towards deregulation will be a tidal wave should the centre-right
opposition win power. The Partido Popular took a lot of pages from the UK
Conservative party book when it debated economic policy at its national
congress in February.
Privatisations will be a key area in which the diminishing presence of the
state may be measured. Outside the think tanks that nurture the Partido
Popular there is not much of a privatisation debate going on but this does
not seem to bother the government which has already embarked upon an
ambitious disposal course. For that matter, Mr Gonzalez's party never
clearly formulated a policy before on what the public sector should look
like.
Repsol, the government-controlled energy group, is to reduce state ownership
to below 50 per cent through a public share offering next month and this
placement will be followed, before the summer, by one in which Argentaria,
the wholly state-owned banking corporation, will place 25 per cent of itself
on the market.
If market conditions are right Tabacalera, the government's tobacco
monopoly, could also make a share offering before the year is out that will
reduce public ownership in the business to below the 50 per cent level.
There are at least three reasons for the rush to privatise by Mr Gonzalez's
team but the ideal of people's capitalism is not one of them. Nor have the
governing socialists been suddenly converted to the idea that private
enterprise is better at running businesses. In all the planned disposals the
state will continue to be the dominant shareholder.
EC deregulatory directives are a consideration but the most important motive
is that the government, which is intent on reducing the budget deficit and
yet faces increasing social security costs as the recession begins to bite,
needs cash. The treasury could raise more than Dollars 2bn this year from
share issues.
A third reason is that privatisation is no longer an English eccentricity:
it has become a European fad. Mr Francisco Luzon, Argentaria's chairman,
boasted last month that Spain was jumping ahead of France and Italy in the
queue to reach global investors.
If Mr Felipe Gonzalez is largely pursuing privatisation by default, the
Partido Popular has embraced the strategy with wholesome conviction. Mr Jose
Maria Aznar, the opposition leader, who wants to bring down taxes and reduce
the budget deficit, says a centre-right government will sell everything it
possibly can.
The Partido Popular's apparent disavowal of state intervention and of the
paternalism that traditionally framed Spanish conservative thinking is a key
political development.
At its national congress the centre-right party also adopted, not without a
certain amount of controversy, a policy called Administracion Unica or
Single Administration, that was proposed by Mr Manuel Fraga, the veteran
conservative who founded the party and who now runs the Galicia, the
autonomous region of north-west Spain. The principle behind the policy is
not unlike that of subsidiarity in the EC.
Mr Fraga broadly proposes to eliminate the duplication between Madrid's
central administration and those of the autonomous communities. The plan is
a blueprint for meaningful devolution to the regions and in one way or
another the Madrid government is going to have address this issue during the
rest of the 1990s.
Whether this will mean rolling back state frontiers or simply reinforcing
them at a mini-state level is another matter.
</TEXT>
