<PROFILE>_AN-DDBB7AHEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930402
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Survey of Spain (12): Polanco enjoys a free hand - The Media
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEDIA moguls should set up shop in Madrid. That is what Mr Jesus Polanco did
and over the past decade he has built up the sort of empire that would raise
alarm bells among anti-trust authorities in other parts of the world.
As chairman of the Prisa group, Mr Polanco controls El Pais, which is by far
the biggest and most influential national newspaper; Sociedad Espanola de
Radiodifusion, SER, the leading commercial radio station; and Canal Plus, a
cable television channel that is now poised to make massive profits.
Mr Polanco has been able to do in Spain what Mr Silvio Berlusconi, for
example, has been barred from from doing in his country. In Italy a group
that has more than a 20 per cent quota of one media sector cannot be present
in another.
Where else, ask critics of the Prisa group, would a media conglomerate be
allowed to corner markets with such blatant impunity? The latest raid of the
Polanco empire has been on a rival commercial radio network called Antena 3
which at one point looked as if it might rock the well-established SER
pre-eminence. Prisa's astute purchase of equity in Antena 3 has apparently
neutralised the threat.
Liquidity has fuelled the group's aggressive growth. El Pais, which sells
over 400,000 copies a day and more than 1m on Sundays, posted 1992 profits
of Pta7.5bn (Dollars 647m) on a turnover of Pta60bn.
Canal Plus, launched less than three years ago and the group's heaviest
investment to date, has pulled in 630,000 subscribers which puts it
comfortably over its break-even point. Prisa's 25 per cent stake in Canal
Plus now looks like the proverbial licence to print money and the group has
announced ambitious satellite television plans.
The free hand that Mr Polanco has enjoyed in his highly successful bid to
penetrate the minds and homes of Spaniards has allowed him to become
possibly the most important man in the country. Government ministers treat
the Prisa group with awe.
El Pais has been a firm friend of the governing socialist party but when its
wide coverage of the Partido Popular's national congress last February
included a soft interview with the party's leader and a favourable editorial
that welcomed the growth of the centre-right opposition there were dark
mutterings in the corridors of power. Had Mr Polanco switched horses?
Mr Polanco and El Pais are probably quite sensibly covering their bets. The
government's unease, nevertheless, pointed to the power that is wielded by
the front-runners in the domestic media.
ABC, which has daily sales of some 280,000 and has been required reading for
Spain's conservatives since the turn of the century, often appears to create
policies for the Partido Popular rather than echo them. The independence of
Barcelona's intelligent La Vanguardia daily so discomforted the local
nationalists that they launched a rival newspaper which, predictably, gained
few readers outside the Catalan government's immediate circle.
With average sales of 230,000 three years after its launch, Madrid's El
Mundo is the fastest growing national newspaper and it has been instrumental
in setting new standards of investigative and hard-hitting journalism that
have benefited the press as a whole. The current illicit party financing
scandal, known as the Filesa case, was first broken by El Mundo nearly two
years ago.
Uncompromisingly censorious of the governing Socialists, El Mundo has
startled El Pais out of its complacency. And mindful of the Prisa group's
power, the brash newcomer to the domestic press sector is also critical of
the influence that Mr Polanco has been allowed to accumulate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
