<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Survey of Spain (4): When a king can decide - Juan Carlos
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOLE explicitly political role that King Juan Carlos is called upon to
play under the terms of the Spanish constitution is to consult the leaders
of the parties that have contested an election and select one of them to be
prime minister. The prospect of a hung parliament later this year is likely
to make the selection process a delicate task, writes Tom Burns.
There is no precedent for such constitutional fine tuning. In the past the
monarch's consultations were a mere formality because in each of the five
previous parliaments of his reign one party, first the Centrists and
subsequently the Socialists, had a clear ascendancy in the legislature.
In the circumstances it is useful that King Juan Carlos' profile should be
riding as high at present as it was at the beginning of the 1980s when his
decisive support of constitutional legality saved Spain's nascent democracy
from a right-wing military coup.
Two recent developments have served to project the king. One is the
publication of an authorised biography, written in the form of an extended
interview, that has become a runaway bestseller. The other mood is of
national grief prompted by the terminal illness over the past few weeks of
Don Juan, Count of Barcelona, the monarch's father.
In the book the king successfully walks a tightrope by being respectful
about General Franco who placed him on the throne and also respectful to his
father who was banished by Franco on account of his liberal views. The dual
theme of the biography has something for everybody: Franco gave the king a
free hand to govern after him as he saw fit and Don Juan, who was to
abdicate his rights in favour of his son, bequeathed to his son both the
legitimate line of succession and the constitutional ideas that he had lived
by.
The passing of Don Juan will be marked by a royal pomp and circumstance that
was absent in 1975 when the king succeeded Franco. The king, who has lately
spent most of his time at his father's bedside, has drawn up plans for a
lying-in-state in the royal palace and a solemn burial in the royal crypt of
the Escorial monastery which has hitherto been reserved for monarchs.
The book, 'El Rey' by Jose Luis de Villalonga, is the king's own version of
recent Spanish history and promotes him as the guarantor of the nation's
stability. Don Juan's funeral will affirm before the Spanish public, for the
first time in generations, the grandeur of the monarchy as an institution.
</TEXT>
