<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Burmah cheer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Optimism ahead of the results from Burmah Castrol proved thoroughly
justified as the group announced profits above most analysts' expectations,
figures which drove Burmah shares up to their best level for more than nine
years.
Burmah's net income came in at Pounds 90.2m, well above the most optimistic
forecasts, as was the dividend. Most analysts pencilled in a current year
forecast of Pounds 100m-plus, following what was described as a very
successful post-results meeting.
Burmah shares, among the market's best performers in the past week, closed
18 higher at 750p, after touching 757p.
British Petroleum shares continued to lose ground, with the market reacting
to hints that a possible blockbusting rights issue may be in the process of
being put together by City merchant banks. It was hinted that the
derivatives market had picked up the scent of an exceptionally large put
trade in the making.
A record-breaking rights issue at BP has long been mooted, although many
analysts take the view that a massive call on shareholders could still be at
least a year away. At the close of trading BP were 6 weaker at 297 1/2 p
with 10m shares dealt.
Recent weakness in Lasmo shares, triggered by what has been seen as a poor
response by institutions to a recent series of post-results presentations,
was arrested as a number of big funds were said to have switched from
Enterprise into Lasmo. The latter edged up 2 1/2 to 158p on 3.7m traded,
while Enterprise weakened 12 to 506p.
</TEXT>
