<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Mixed trend as doubts arise
over jobless data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices ended with no clear trend in moderate trading yesterday,
after an unexpectedly poor set of jobless claims data had raised worries
that today's March employment report would reveal renewed weakness in the
labour market, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 4.33 at 3,439.44. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 finished 1.37 down at 450.30, while the American SE
composite ended 0.66 easier at 422.77 and the Nasdaq composite 3.49 off at
686.64. New York SE volume came to 234.5m shares.
There was no follow-through from Wednesday's late declines, primarily
because the selling was attributed to institutional investors unwinding
options positions in listed and over-the-counter stocks.
The market, in fact, was resilient, brushing off the morning's employment
news, which showed a much larger than expected 33,000 rise in weekly jobless
claims. Normally, the figures might have frightened investors, because they
suggested that the labour market continues to struggle in spite of recent
improvements in economic growth.
Investors, however, chose to wait for today's more important and revealing
March employment report. Analysts are expecting it to show a rise of between
75,000 and 100,000 in non-farm payrolls. If the figure comes in well below
that range, then the sell-off that might have followed yesterday's jobless
claims release could be triggered.
The day's other main piece of economic news - a small decline in the
National Association of Purchasing Management's March index of business
activity - had little discernible impact on market sentiment, although the
figures added to other recent data which suggest that economic growth in the
first quarter may have slowed from the strong rates seen at the end of 1992.
Drug shares featured again. After posting gains early on Wednesday on
reports that the Clinton administration may not, after all, consider
imposing controls on pharmaceuticals prices, many of the leading issues have
run into concerted selling.
Among the biggest stocks, Pfizer fell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 61 1/8 ,
Merck slipped Dollars 1 to Dollars 34 3/8 , Johnson &amp; Johnson receded
Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 40 3/4 and Schering-Plough lost Dollars 1 to
Dollars 59.
Cable television stocks tumbled after the Fed Communications Commission
voted to set a benchmark for prices charged by the industry. Cablevision
fell Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 36 1/4 , Time Warner Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars
33, Comcast Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 20 7/8 and TCI Dollars 2 to Dollars 20
1/2 .
Merrill Lynch advanced Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 72 1/8 in busy trading on
figures which showed that it had retained its position in the first quarter
as the biggest underwriter of stock and bonds in the US.
On the Nasdaq market, leading technology issues were mixed. Microsoft gained
Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 93 and Apple Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 51 3/4 , but
Intel lost Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 111 1/2 .
Canada
TORONTO posted a modest gain after active trading. The TSE 300 index
finished 12.1 higher at 3,614.5 and advances led declines by 395 to 292
after volume of 66.8m shares.
Talisman Energy said a venture with Amoco Canada Petroleum reported a major
wildcat gas discovery in the Sukunka in British Columbia. The stock rose
CDollars 1 to CDollars 20 1/4 .
</TEXT>
