<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / World Stock Markets (South Africa): Golds put industrials in
shadow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM COCHRANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JOHANNESBURG drifted lower following Wednesday's hectic trade. The overall
index, down 15 at 3,544, incorporated falls of 13 to 4,413 in industrials
and 14 to 1,191 in golds.
This followed a chart-topping performance for the market over the first
three months of 1993. South Africa led the FT-Actuaries World Indices, both
in sterling and US dollar terms, with gains of 19.65 and 18.97 per cent
respectively.
The figures reflect recovery in the financial rand, up 7 per cent against
the dollar and 9 per cent against sterling this year, after a 34 per cent
drop against the dollar in 1992. In local currency terms, South African
equities still managed a rise of 11.14 per cent.
The overall index performance masks the conflict between gold mining stocks
and a muted industrial sector. By the end of March the JSE Gold index was up
51 per cent over three months, against a 1 per cent gain in industrials.
Brokers were saying yesterday that there could be more to come in golds,
which have attracted income funds and gold funds from around the world in
pursuit of the high dividend yields available, and the assumed protection
from international strife. 'Even today you can get yields of 10 per cent,
net of withhold-ing tax,' commented one broker yesterday.
</TEXT>
