<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Era of market support pacts for
commodities may be over
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY'S VOTE against any renegotiation of the international rubber
agreement (Inra) and Wednesday's collapse of talks on a new international
coffee agreement appear to be the final nails in the coffin of those
commodity pacts which attempt to support market prices.
Only two weeks ago delegates to the International Cocoa Organisation (ICCO)
abandoned their attempts to negotiate a pact based on a stock withholding
scheme. They are now planning an agreement described by one official as more
than purely administrative, but well short of a full economic accord.
Both the cocoa and coffee agreements have been moribund for several years.
Under the present agreement, which runs out in September, the ICCO was using
a buffer stock scheme in its attempts to shore up prices.
The system came to an end early in 1988 when the stock reached its maximum
permitted level of 250,000 tonnes. Members remain anxious to have some sort
of agreement put in place in order to avoid the threat to the market of any
sudden sale of the buffer stock, which still holds more than 230,000 tonnes
of cocoa.
The International Coffee Organisation was supporting prices through an
export quota system, but that collapsed in July 1989, sending world prices
crashing.
The latest London talks failed over a relatively minor point, indicating
that the gulf between producers and consumers has not narrowed in the
ensuing years. While the present agreement expires at the end of September,
it is possible that it could be extended by a further year.
The International Rubber Organisation announced yesterday that a majority of
its members, led by consumer countries, were against renegotiating their
pact, which expires at the end of the year. Consumers voted against because
they believe producers have failed to abide by the price review provisions
of the present agreement.
Inro will meet in May to consider the future of the agreement, but producers
have said they will oppose any extension without a decision to start
negotiations on a new pact.
Mr Lawrence Eagles, analyst with GNI, the London futures brokers, said that
the virtually simultaneous collapse of the coffee and rubber agreements
showed that there was no longer any will among G7 countries to give aid to
developing countries through price support systems.
Another observer said yesterday that the biggest change in attitude towards
commodity agreements was the realisation that, if the existing ones had not
worked, any established in future did not stand much chance of working
either.
'It has taken years for that message to sink home,' he said. 'People are now
wondering if they should bother with the bureaucracy, the expense, and the
effort.'
The last 10 days of talks at the ICO - one of many similar meetings over the
last 12 months - are believed to have cost around Pounds 500,000. But the
pace of the negotiations was always, in the memorable words of one delegate,
'like a snail on Mogadon.'
Nevertheless, the world coffee markets have had to keep one eye on the
endless rounds of negotiation. Mr Peter Kettle, analyst with ED &amp; F. Man,
the London trade house, said earlier this week that, even though the markets
always expected nothing positive to emerge from the ICO, they were
inevitably disappointed when nothing did so prices were marked down
accordingly.
Yesterday one London coffee trader said that the talks had been a deterrent
to trading.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P0179 Fruits and Tree Nuts, NEC.
</IN>
