<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Indian vegetable oil exports
set to start
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KUNAL BOSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CALCUTTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDIA - until a few years ago a big importer of vegetable oils - may decide
to allow exports following a bumper oilseeds crop.
The country already exports minor oils. Sales of them are expected to be
about 8,000 tonnes, worth Rs300m (USDollars 9.6m), in the fiscal year ending
March 31.
An oil surplus of over 500,000 tonnes is expected after meeting the domestic
requirement of nearly 7m tonnes, making the export of major oils like
soyabean, sunflower and groundnut seem likely.
The record combined summer and winter oilseeds production of 21.6m tonnes,
compared with 19.5m tonnes last year, will enable the country to earn
Rs13.62bn from the export of oilmeals, oilseeds and minor oils.
India has achieved self-reliance in oils at a low level of per capita
consumption of 6.8 kg, compared with the world average of about 15 kg.
India has the option to import 300,000 tonnes of palm oil from Malaysia but
the government has announced that India will not be importing oils in the
current 'oil year' which began in November 1992. At the same time prices of
all types of oils have fallen sharply because of the comfortable supply
situation.
The breakthrough in oilseeds production in India has come about following
the constitution of the Technology Mission on Oilseeds (TMO) in 1986 with
the mandate to provide modern technology, inputs and services to the 7m
farmers who mostly have small holdings.
TMO also has to contend with the fact that nearly 80 per cent of the 24m
hectares of land under oilseeds depends on rain. In this situation, the
small farmers could avail themselves of the 'critical farm services and
inputs' either by becoming members of co-operatives or by doing contract
farming for corporations.
While the co-operative movement has taken deep roots in the oilseeds
economy, ITC, an associate of British American Tobacco, has created a model
for other corporations by producing hybrid oilseeds, conducting farm
extension services, guaranteeing the off-take of seeds from farmers at
remunerative prices and operating an oil refinery.
To ITC goes the credit for popularising sunflower cultivation in Andhra
Pradesh and Karnataka. The government, meanwhile, has helped sustain
farmers' interest in oilseeds cultivation through its market intervention
operation.
</TEXT>
