FT  02 APR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOLD and precious metals were generally easier on the London bullion market
on light profit-taking after Wednesday's rush of excitement. Charts indicate
that the time is right for gold to break out into a higher range, possibly
with an upside target of Dollars 344 a troy ounce, according to dealers.
'But there will be a lot of resistance,' said one. Heavy overhead supplies
are still a factor, but the ease with which the market absorbed sales has
been impressive. BASE METALS mostly remained steady on the LME, with
stability in dollar contracts reflecting the weakness of the dollar in
currency markets. Three-month ZINC remained boxed in a Dollars 5 range with
an earlier move down to four-week lows of Dollars 995 a tonne finding
expected support. The subsequent recovery failed seriously to test
resistance above Dollars 1,000. COPPER was bolstered by its ability to hold
above Dollars 2,160 support. London's robusta COFFEE futures ended with
severely pared gains after a short covering rally which followed the
breakdown of ICO talks on Wednesday was seen to be overdone.
