<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Government Bonds: German paper weakens after Bundesbank
disappoints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank's decision to leave the key German interest rates unchanged
after yesterday's council meeting proved a big disappointment for the German
government bond market and bund prices ended the day weaker.
Dealers said that even the release of poor industrial production figures
yesterday did nothing to revive the bund market.
'A lot of people had been hoping for a cut in the Lombard and discount rates
and there was a lot of disappointment,' said one trader.
The DTB June long bund future fell to 95.07 by late afternoon from 95.47 in
the morning and against its previous close of 95.38.
Separately, the Bundesbank said it would increase the issue of 7 1/8 per
cent bonds due 2002 by DM2bn bringing the total size of the issue up to
DM16bn.
UK government bonds continued their post-auction rally yesterday morning but
fell back later in the day on profit-taking, ending up to a quarter of a
point lower.
The rally followed a better-than-expected auction of Pounds 3bn of 20-year
stock on Wednesday, and enabled the Bank of England to sell a further Pounds
600m tranche of 10-year stock.
The Bank supplied Pounds 600m of 8 per cent Treasury stock due 2003, mostly
at 52 7/32 only a few hours after the tranche was made available to the
market. The June long gilt futures settled  5/16 down at 106.04.
US Treasury prices fell at the long end of the maturity range yesterday
despite a stronger-than-expected jobless claims report.
In late trading the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  9/16 at 101
29/32 , yielding 6.969 per cent. At the short end of the market, however,
the two-year note was steady at 99 13/16 , to yield 3.957 per cent.
Prices opened mostly firmer, aided by the release of the weekly jobless
claims data, which showed a rise of 33,000 in the number of people claiming
state unemployment insurance.
The news initially buoyed sentiment, because it suggested that tomorrow's
employment report for March would show a similar weakness in the labour
market.
Longer-dated Treasuries, however, were unable to hang on to their gains.
Dealers said there were several factors behind the selling, including
concern about the weak dollar, which could revive inflationary pressures;
another rise in commodity prices; and an unwillingness among traders and
investors to take on too much inventory ahead of today's March employment
numbers.
With most of the selling concentrated at the long end of the market as
dealers unwound some yield curve-flattening trades, shorter-dated prices
held their ground.
ITALIAN government bonds closed lower, hit by the weak lira, political
worries, and heavy supply. However, despite the poor background, dealers
expressed relief that yesterday's auction of government bonds was fully
covered.
The net yield at the auction of 10-year Treasury fixed-rate bonds (BTPs)
rose to 11.56 per cent from 11.36 per cent previously and a total of
L2,500bn of bonds was sold.
The BTP future fell from 94.37 to 93.90 yesterday, as dealers said the
lira's weakness upset the market. The lira traded at 996.00 against the
D-Mark, from around 990.
DEALERS reported healthy demand at yesterday's auction of Spanish government
bonds, and bond prices ended the day little changed despite the new supply.
The Treasury sold a total of Pta1,100bn of three, five and 10-year bonds and
dealers said the relatively high cover - the ratio of bids to the amount
allocated - was seen as an encouraging sign for the market.
DENMARK was the top-performing government bond market last month, with a
return of 4.11 per cent in local currency terms, according to figures
compiled by J. P. Morgan Securities.
Danish bonds rallied in March as pressure on the kroner abated and the
Danish central bank was able to lower its key interest rates. France and
Spain ranked after Denmark with gains of 2.79 per cent and 2.12 per cent
respectively in March.
The French bond market took its cue from the strength of the franc against
the D-Mark in the wake of the conservative coalition's sweeping election
victory and hopes of an easing in monetary policy.
The Bank of Spain's cut in overnight interest rates helped to boost the
Spanish bond market.
Australia was the best-performing market in the first quarter with a return
of 7.29 per cent in local currency terms. For US-dollar based investors, UK
government bonds made the strongest gains, with a return of 6.9 per cent in
March.
</TEXT>
