<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Capital Markets: Pilkington brings issue of
sterling warrant bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PILKINGTON, the UK glass group, yesterday brought the first sterling warrant
bond issue in six years, raising Pounds 95m to refinance its purchase last
month of the glass processing and distribution business of Heywood Williams.
The decision to issue bonds with equity warrants attached rather than
convertible bonds owed much to the high yield on Pilkington's shares, which
yesterday stood at around 6.4 per cent.
To attract investors into convertibles, issuers of the recent spate of
sterling convertible bonds have generally to offer a yield 3 per cent or
more higher than their equity yield. That would have made the financing
costs to Pilkington unattractive, according to one person close to the
issue.
The five-year bonds issued yesterday carry a coupon of 7 1/2 per cent and
were priced to yield 175 basis points over gilts. The warrants attached to
the bonds were issued with an exercise price of 120p - close to yesterday's
close of 116p - and can be converted into 78.2m Pilkington shares,
equivalent to around 10 per cent of the outstanding equity.
The high level of volatility in Pilkington's shares in recent months has
boosted the implied volatility levels used to value the equity warrants,
making them more valuable to investors. As a result, the premium associated
with the warrants amounted to Pounds 18.5m.
Under new UK accounting rules due to be introduced soon, such a premium can
be taken into shareholders funds. According to one analyst yesterday, this
would reduce Pilkington's gearing from 90 per cent to 74 per cent.
The bonds and warrants, which will be traded separately or as a package,
were said by banks not involved in the deal to have met strong demand,
particularly from continental European investors.
Partly as a result of switching by investors, Pilkington's share price fell
back to 116p yesterday, from 125p at the beginning of the day.
</TEXT>
