<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Bonds: Latin American borrowers raise Dollars
and D-Mark funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NUMBER of Latin American borrowers tapped the international capital
markets yesterday, raising both dollar and D-Mark funds.
In the D-Mark sector, Venezuela launched a DM150m five-year issue, via
Commerzbank. The bonds carried a 10 1/4 per cent coupon which proved
attractive to European retail investors, as well as specialist Latin
American fund managers.
The double-digit coupon and wide spread of more than 400 basis points over
the five-year bund yield was seen as sufficient compensation for buying what
is currently viewed as a very risky credit.
The uncertain political situation in Venezuela, ahead of elections at the
end of the year, has caused substantial volatility in Venezuela's par bonds
which are now trading at less than 60 cents in the dollar.
Also in D-Marks, the Inter-American Development Bank launched a 10-year deal
priced to yield 13 basis points over the comparable Bund yield.
The deal, arranged by Deutsche Bank, met some demand in the Far East, as
Japanese investors returned to the market at the start of their new fiscal
year.
Meanwhile, Uruguay is expected to launch its second Eurobond issue today,
following its return to the market last year.
The five-year deal, arranged by Chase, is expected to total Dollars 75m, but
could be increased to Dollars 100m.
The price talk is for a launch spread of 220 to 230 basis points above the
five-year US Treasury yield, a more aggressive pricing than had been
suggested when the deal was first mandated, but several dealers reported
demand at that level.
Meanwhile, a Dollars 130m five-year issue for Controladora Comercial
Mexicana, a Mexican retailer, arranged by Citibank, met strong demand.
Dealers said the spread of 370 basis points over the five-year Treasury
yield appeared generous, and the deal was oversubscribed.
Also in the sector, Argentina's Banco Medefin launched a small Dollars 30m
one-year deal, via Credit Lyonnais.
In the Australian dollar market, Shell Australia launched the first issue
since the Labor party's recent election victory. The Dollars 100m five-year
deal was arranged by Hambros Bank.
</TEXT>
