<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Capital Markets: Stock lending business
benefits from tax ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN AMENDMENT to tax regulations aimed at keeping international stock lending
business in London was announced yesterday by Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial
secretary to the Treasury.
The ability to borrow stock is essential for financial houses whose trading
strategies involve them in selling securities they do not own, making it one
of the key services underpinning London's active international equity
market.
The business has been hindered by the tax treatment of so-called
'manufactured dividends' - dividends which are paid to the lender of stock.
These have been subjected to a withholding tax in the past, which cannot be
recovered by an overseas lender which has no UK tax liability against which
to offset the charge.
Following discussions between the Inland Revenue and the City's Stock
Borrowing and Lending Committee, headed by Mr Ian Plenderleith, a director
of the Bank of England, such dividends will now be paid gross to overseas
lenders, it was announced. A similar ruling on the payment of dividends to
UK-based lenders was made two years ago.
The restriction that overseas stock can only pass through one intermediary
between borrower and lender is to be lifted, and a wider range of market
participants will be authorised to borrow stock, rather than just the
marketmakers and 'quasi-marketmakers' who are currently recognised. The new
rules apply only to overseas securities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
