<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Hyundai shipyard weathers bleak
forecasts - John Burton visits HHI shipbuilders in Ulsan during a period of
structural transition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The frantic activity at Hyundai Heavy Industries' shipbuilding yard in Ulsan
appears to belie a recent forecast by the Federation of Korean Industries
that shipbuilders face the bleakest future among the nation's main
businesses this year.
The FKI cited an excessive supply of ships and a downturn in the global
shipping industry to support its prediction of a slowdown in orders.
Although the ships being built by Hyundai Heavy Industries at the world's
largest shipyard were ordered during the past few years, its officials
believe that new orders will be able to keep its seven dry docks occupied.
'We are expecting good years in both 1994 and 1995,' says Mr K. H. Lee of
the ship sales department.
Orders fell to Dollars 750m last year from Dollars 3.1bn in 1991. 'We regard
last year and this year as a period of structural transition that will lead
to a recovery in the mid-1990s,' Mr Lee adds.
One reason for the optimism is that HHI is shifting toward the production of
more advanced and profitable vessels, such as gas carriers and large
container ships, while reducing its dependence on tankers and bulk carriers.
It plans to build passenger cruise ships within the next few years.
It launched its first liquefied natural gas carrier in February and the
vessel will be delivered next March to Hyundai Merchant Marine, a sister
subsidiary in the Hyundai group. A second LNG vessel is being built for
Yukong Line, a Korean shipping company.
This follows the construction of 13 liquefied petroleum gas carriers since
1986, with four more on order.
HHI expects to deliver 34 ships with a total value of Dollars 1.9bn this
year, against 26 vessels worth Dollars 1.7bn in 1992. The company has built
530 ships since 1973, when the Ulsan yards were opened.
HHI has reported a significant improvement in earnings in the past two
years, making it the most profitable unit among the 41 companies in the
Hyundai industrial group.
Profits reached Won281.2bn (Dollars 239m) on estimated sales of Won2,400bn
last year having climbed from Won33.9bn in 1990 to Won206.7bn in 1991. It
has set a sales target of Won3,250bn for 1993.
The higher profits reflect a cessation of labour strife that convulsed the
yard between 1987 and 1990, when it was a centre of the country's trade
union movement that emerged after the downfall of the military dictatorship.
The absence of industrial action since 1990 has led to an increase in
productivity among the company's 22,000 workers.
Privately-held HHI is eligible for a listing on the Seoul stock market since
it has reported at least three successive years of profits, a condition for
a public offering in Korea.
State approval for a Won270bn share issue, which was requested in September,
has been delayed because HHI has become embroiled in a political dispute
between the government and Mr Chung Ju-yung, the founder of the Hyundai
conglomerate, after he unsuccessfully stood for president last year.
HHI has been accused by the government of providing illegal campaign funds
for Mr Chung's presidential campaign and Mr Choi Soo-il, HHI president, is
in prison awaiting a possible trial for his alleged role in the affair.
Hyundai claims the government is preventing HHI and other Hyundai companies
from directly tapping the equity market because of its hostility towards Mr
Chung.
HHI acknowledges that the threat posed by emerging shipbuilding nations,
such as China, is forcing it to reduce its dependence on ship construction.
While shipbuilding accounts for 60 per cent of sales and almost all of its
profits, according to analysts, HHI wants to reduce the sales ratio to 50
per cent by 1995 and 40 per cent by 2000.
Two thirds of its Dollars 350m capital investment budget this year is
devoted to expanding production in its three non-core sectors, including
industrial plants, engines and machinery, and offshore facilities.
Offshore business has been lifted by orders worth Dollars 1bn placed last
year by the Oil and Natural Gas Commission of India for platforms and
undersea pipelines and other sales in Canada and China.
The industrial plant division is expanding into environmental projects,
including the production of water sewage plants. The engine division is
developing a gas turbine engine that will be used in LNG ships and other
vessels.
</TEXT>
