<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Maruti suffers from fall in
exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MARUTI Udyog, a vehicle-making joint venture between the Indian government
and Suzuki Motor of Japan, has reported a fall in pre-tax profits to Rs342m
(Dollars 11m) for 1992, down from Rs350m the year before, writes Shiraz
Sidhva in New Delhi.
The Indian government allowed the Japanese car maker to increase its stake
to 50 per cent last June from 40 per cent. Mr R. C. Bhargava, managing
director, said exports of the company's 800cc car fell to 14,595 vehicles
from 22,921 last year, largely because of the war in the former Yugoslavia
and the 40 per cent devaluation of the Italian lira. Foreign exchange
earnings fell to Dollars 56.7m from Dollars 92.2m.
Maruti Udyog plans to begin exporting to South America. Suzuki's export
strategy ensures that the Indian company is the only source for its 800cc
car, which is sold in Hungary, France, the Netherlands, Spain, Poland and
Portugal.
Demand in India for the Maruti car expanded, with the company selling
126,854 vehicles in 1992 against 122,438 the year before.
