<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Fletcher to sell 9% of its stake
in Canadian arm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FLETCHER Challenge, the New Zealand forestry group, is to sell 9 per cent of
its stake in Fletcher Challenge Canada for CDollars 190.8m (USDollars
151.7m), through a public offering of shares.
The move is part of FCL's debt reduction programme and will reduce its
shareholding in the Canadian subsidiary to 63 per cent.
FCL said a primary aim of the sale, however, was to avoid having to issue
120m of its own ordinary shares on July 16 when it was liable to convert
shares in Fletcher Challenge Investments, a Canadian subsidiary, into its
own.
Mr Hugh Fletcher, chief executive, said FCL wanted to avoid converting the
shares because this would dilute the value of its ordinary shares.
He said a group of Canadian underwriters, led by Wood Gundy, would buy 10.6m
A shares in Fletcher Challenge Canada. The group would offer the shares to
the public for CDollars 190.8m, or CDollars 18 a share, on an instalment
basis.
The purchase price would be paid to FCL in two instalments of CDollars
100.7m on April 28, and CDollars 90.1m on June 30 next year.
Mr Fletcher said the transaction would enhance shareholder value by
increasing asset backing per share.
FCL will earn a profit on the deal. The price of CDollars 18 a share
compares with CDollars 14.50 that FCL paid for the shares last year.
Analysts said the move accorded with FCL's objective of reducing its
exposure to the British Columbian forestry industry, although Mr Fletcher
emphasised its long-term commitment to the Canadian industry, and optimism
about its future.
