<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: S&amp;P cuts debt rating at top
Finnish banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNION Bank of Finland and Kansallis-Osake-Pankki, Finland's two leading
commercial banks, yesterday had their debt ratings cut by Standard &amp; Poor's,
the US ratings agency, as a result of the continuing crisis in the Finnish
economy.
S&amp;P lowered its senior ratings of both banks from BBB plus to BBB and their
subordinated debt ratings from BBB to BBB minus.
It said the decision reflected the impact of the weak Finnish economy on the
banks' asset quality and financial performance.
KOP suffered a FM3.7bn (Dollars 6.16m) loss in 1992, while Unitas, the
holding company for UBF, reported a FM2.7bn deficit.
'With the economy likely to remain depressed for a prolonged period, high
levels of credit write-offs and non-performing loans will persist into the
medium-term,' S&amp;P said.
It said that the Finnish parliament's strong commitment to supporting the
banking sector meant that the outlook for both KOP and UBF was now stable.
