<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Japan sends warning on attempted
coercion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S Fair Trade Commission yesterday warned leading banks and brokers it
would closely monitor their entry into new business areas to ensure there
were no violations of anti-monopoly laws.
The FTC, issuing its first guidelines for the financial industry, warned
that banks must not use their influence with corporate clients to coerce
them to do business with a new securities subsidiary. The warning also
applies to brokers opening a trust banking subsidiary.
Commission officials and many brokers are concerned that leading banks will
be able to coax their customers to ensure the new subsidiaries will have a
steady stream of business, but it will be up to the FTC to distinguish
between coaxing and coercing.
The FTC said anti-monopoly laws would be violated if a parent bank provided
services to a customer on the understanding that the customer would use its
new broking subsidiary. Attempts to prevent a customer from doing business
with a competitor would be a violation.
The FTC is likely to demand information from banks and brokers establishing
subsidiaries to ensure that the structure complies with the financial reform
legislation.
The commission will have difficulty tracing informal links among Japanese
corporate groups which help determine choices. Some bank customers will feel
an obligation to shift bond business to a new subsidiary.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
