<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Kodak files patent suit against
Sony
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EASTMAN Kodak has filed a suit against Sony, one of Japan's leading
electronics manufacturers, in a patent infringement dispute that could have
broad implications throughout the consumer electronics industry.
Kodak alleges that Sony's video cassette recorders, camcorders (video
cameras) and other audio and video recording products infringe a patent the
US company obtained in 1981 covering a new type of recording head for
magnetic recording devices.
Industry analysts say the same technology is widely used throughout the
consumer electronics industry. Kodak declined to comment on whether it has
granted patent licences to other manufacturers.
According to the complaint, filed in Texas, Kodak has been attempting to
reach a licensing agreement with Sony since the late 1980s. It is asking the
court to issue an injunction to prevent Sony from selling products in the US
that allegedly infringe its patent.
The US company is also seeking treble damages, although it does not specify
the amount, and has asked for a jury trial. Sony's sales in the US last year
were over Dollars 6bn, of which VCRs and video cameras represented a
significant portion. Sony America declined to comment on the suit.
The damages covered by the Kodak claim could be substantial, said Mr Jack
Kelly of Goldman Sachs. He said the suit against Sony might encourage other
manufacturers of recording equipment to seek licences from Kodak.
</TEXT>
