<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Nestle considers listing on NYSE
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLE, the world's largest foods group, is considering applying to have its
shares listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
'We are very interested,' Mr Francois Perroux, the group spokesman,
confirmed yesterday, but he did not expect a decision within the next few
weeks.
Mr Perroux said Nestle overcame the main obstacle three years ago, when it
began to publish accounts according to international accounting standards.
Its 1992 accounts will take an important step further towards US-style full
disclosure by publishing for the first time a breakdown of profits by
business segment.
Last week, when the group published its preliminary 1992 results, it
revealed it would submit a plan for simplifying its three-tier share
structure to the annual general meeting on May 27.
Under this scheme, both the participation certificates and the bearer shares
would be converted into registered shares.
'The board is convinced this measure will render Nestle shares even more
attractive to institutional investors,' the group said.
Mr Perroux said that the share structure simplification would also mean that
the group's two US deposit receipt programmes could be merged into one.
Many large European companies have become increasingly interested in foreign
share listings in recent years, as they anticipate their needs for capital
outstripping the capacity of local markets to provide it.
Earlier this week, Daimler-Benz of Germany said that it had reached
agreement with the US Securities &amp; Exchange Commission that would lead to a
listing of its shares in New York later this year.
Deutsche Bank, Germany's largest bank, has also expressed interest.
</TEXT>
