<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: Dresdner's 13% rise in line with
forecasts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DRESDNER BANK, Germany's second biggest bank, yesterday became the last of
the country's 'big five' banks to report a healthy rise in profits for last
year.
Dresdner's total operating profits - which include a contribution from
own-account trading - rose by 13.1 per cent to DM2.81bn (Dollars 1.74bn), in
line with analysts' expectations.
The results follow a 7 per cent increase in Deutsche Bank's operating
profits, a 20 per cent increase at Commerzbank, and high rates of growth at
Bayerische Vereinsbank and Hypo-Bank.
Mr Wolfgang Roller, who next month will step down as chief executive, said
that in the first two months of the current year profits were 'slightly
ahead' of the high level of January and February last year.
Mr Roller said provisions against bad and doubtful debts had increased
substantially over the course of the last year.
Dresdner's figures were driven by a 7.4 per cent increase in net interest
income which rose DM399m to DM5.79bn. Reflecting lively securities business,
net commission income climbed 16 per cent to DM2.3bn. Operating expenses
rose by 9.6 per cent.
Mr Roller said the bank reduced its loans to problem countries from DM5.5bn
in 1991 to DM4.5bn last year, with DM3.4bn provided for.
Provisions for loans to the former Soviet Union were increased from 80 per
cent to 90 per cent of the total.
Net earnings rose DM314m to DM966m, an increase of 48 per cent, of which
DM466m was transferred to reserves. This figure includes loan-loss
provisions against what the bank called 'the unsatisfactory risk situation
over the broad range of lending business'.
None of the banks give a figure for loan provisioning, as is allowed under
German accounting rules, but disclosure will have to be made in the current
year figures under a new European Community accounting directive.
Mr Roller said the clear priority for last year had been to increase
provisions over transfers to reserves and dividend payment: for that reason
the bank was paying an unchanged dividend of DM12 per share. Earlier this
week the bank announced a two-for-19 rights issue at DM350 per share, which
will raise DM1.4bn.
</TEXT>
