<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / International Company News: BNP fall reflects gloom in
French banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANQUE Nationale de Paris, the state-controlled bank which is poised for
privatisation by France's new conservative government, saw net profits fall
by 26 per cent to FFr2.17bn (Dollars 396m) last year from FFr2.94bn in 1991,
reflecting the gloom in the French financial sector.
The bank is also cutting its dividend to FFr7.50 from FFr10.50.
BNP was affected by the general pressures on the French banking sector. Net
banking income rose by 5.2 per cent to FFr39.92bn from FFr37.93bn, with
operating profits up by 8.9 per cent to FFr11.81bn from FFr10.85bn over the
same period.
Mr Rene Thomas, chairman, said the group had been hit by the sluggish state
of the banking market and by the sharp increase in bank borrowing costs
towards the end of the year, when short-term interest rates escalated during
the Bank of France's battle to defend the franc.
However, the chief problem for the bank was the impact of the economic
slowdown on its property portfolio and also on its smaller corporate
clients.
The group raised net provisions to FFr8.38bn from FFr8.08bn in 1991.
It made new provisions of FFr10.14bn, but recouped FFr1.76bn of write-downs
made in previous years on loans to developing countries.
</TEXT>
