<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / UK Company News: Route into Europe is on the cards - Unigate
and its interests in continental expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN MR Ross Buckland became chief executive of Unigate two-and-a-half years
ago, the sprawling group was described by one observer as 'a business which,
if it didn't exist, nobody would have wanted to invent.'
From its dairy industry roots, Unigate had spread into areas as varied as
trade exhibitions, US fast-food restaurants, car auctions, road freight and
large-scale poultry breeding.
The supposed logic for this diversification - a balanced earnings portfolio
 -was belied by an increasingly dismal profits performance.
Mr Buckland, an Australian who formerly headed the European operations of
Kellogg, the US breakfast cereals company, has worked hard to give a more
coherent shape to the group. Declaring food and distribution to be its core
businesses, he has set about shedding operations which were performing
poorly or had limited potential for development.
The loss-plagued JP Wood chicken subsidiary was acquired by Hillsdown
Holdings for Pounds 30m last year. Unigate's unprofitable contract car hire
business is being wound down, its US cheese unit has been sold, and its
American restaurant chain is being prepared for possible flotation on the US
stock market this summer. Further disposals are likely, Mr Buckland says.
Meanwhile, Unigate has hit the acquisition trail. A Pounds 17m bid for some
of the Co-operative Wholesale Society's milk businesses in January was
followed by a Pounds 50.4m friendly offer for Clifford Foods, a
Berkshire-based dairy and juice company, and the Pounds 54m purchase of
Glass Glover, which operates warehouses and distribution for large UK
retailers.
This flurry of activity has yet to produce a convincing improvement in
pre-tax profits, which fell slightly in the first half of this year.
Nonetheless, the stock market seems to believe a corner of some sort has
been turned. After sliding steeply last summer, Unigate's share price has
rebounded since the autumn.
The Co-op and Clifford deals are expected to boost Unigate's profits in the
next couple of years by enabling it to use dairy capacity more efficiently.
The Glass Glover purchase, while generously priced, will broaden Unigate's
distribution franchise with big supermarket groups by adding warehouse
contracts.
It is much less clear, though, that Unigate has yet found a formula for
sustained longer-term growth. Though its distribution arm is regarded as
efficient and well-managed, warehouse management is a relatively mature
business which offers limited opportunities for scale economies.
The recent expansion of Unigate's liquid milk operations - which the group
spent the 1980s trying to de-emphasise - looks to most observers like a
defensive attempt to secure competitive position in a business which is a
handy source of cash.
UK liquid milk consumption has been declining steadily by a percentage point
a year, while doorstep deliveries are losing sales to supermarkets at a
considerably faster rate. Though Mr Buckland expects these trends to
stabilise in the next few years, he concedes that the profits outlook for
liquid milk is hardly electrifying.
So where will the growth come from? Mr Buckland says part of the answer lies
in moving Unigate's food-processing operations into higher value-added
areas. He points to the recent expansion of dairy desserts output and the
Pounds 15m invested in the past three years to double capacity and produce
more cooked meats at its Malton bacon factory, which has won back market
share from imports.
However, profits on these operations fell in the first half due to
recession, higher pig prices and increased marketing costs. Meanwhile, St
Ivel Gold, which pioneered the market for low-fat spreads and is the
company's biggest brand, has seen its sales stagnate and faces fierce price
competition.
Unigate's recent performance in yoghurt, another main product line, has also
been undistinguished. Since the late 1980s Muller, a small German dairy
company, has captured almost 20 per cent of the UK market by offering an
innovative range of yoghurts at premium prices. Muller is now the 26th
largest UK supermarket brand, well ahead of St Ivel Shape yoghurt.
Asked why Unigate allowed itself to be trounced on its home ground, Mr
Buckland throws up his hands and exclaims: 'Mea culpa] All of us in the UK
failed to make the right judgement. Muller was fundamentally not seen as a
threat by established yogurt producers. The consumer saw things differently
and said, l like Muller's products.'
Unigate is now making yogurts intended to match the German company's range.
Recently, Mr Buckland's horizons have begun to extend beyond the UK to
continental Europe. An important objective in re-shaping the dairy and
distribution businesses, he says, has been to build a domestic base solid
enough to support the risks inherent in overseas expansion.
He says Unigate is interested in pursuing continental joint ventures or
acquisitions of more than Pounds 50m. He sees particularly good
opportunities in private-label manufacturing, which he thinks is set to grow
rapidly as food retailers in Europe become steadily more powerful.
He would fund acquisitions by making further disposals, if necessary, to
avoid the need for a rights issue or a further increase in Unigate's
gearing, which stands at about 60 per cent.
One possible route to the continent lies through Nutricia, a Dutch babyfood
and clinical nutrition company of which Unigate owns a third. Unigate, which
acquired its original stake when it sold its Cow &amp; Gate division to Nutricia
in 1981, purchased further shares last year.
Mr Buckland, who sits on Nutricia's board, says relations with the Dutch
company have grown much closer recently, and both sides are interested in
strengthening their links further.
Could an eventual full takeover of Nutricia - which has a stock market
valuation of more than Pounds 400m - be on the cards?
Mr Buckland's answer is intriguingly equivocal. Unigate would never consider
a hostile bid, which could in any case be easily frustrated under Dutch
takeover rules. However, he also says: 'The relationship has not been
static. Don't be surprised if it doesn't remain static for the next 18
months.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
