<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / All change in foreign exchanges: The nature of international
currency dealing has altered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Who pushed sterling out of the European exchange rate mechanism last year
and brought chaos to the currency markets?
Most people point the finger at young dealers in commercial banks - the boys
in red braces - trading millions of pounds per second. But the world's
central banks are coming up with a different answer.
Their evidence suggests the men in grey suits - investment fund and pension
fund managers - make the really big decisions in currency markets. And there
are signs that these investors - backed by massive funds and portfolios -
are changing the nature of currency dealing in a way that may pose problems
for governments and banks.
Until 10 years ago, foreign exchange dealing was dominated by large numbers
of commercial banks and big corporations, trading currencies mainly for
their own books. But in the late 1980s, the foreign exchange business
attracted investment institutions with huge portfolios.
The deregulation of the world's financial markets encouraged these funds to
broaden their activities across the globe. Some invested directly in the
currency market, believing that exchange rate movements made currencies as
profitable as other financial instruments. Others bought currencies to hedge
the exposure of their underlying foreign assets.
Overall, the flows generated by investment institutions are far greater than
those that the banks are prepared to risk. A currency dealing room in a big
London bank will have tens of million of pounds with which to operate on any
one day. But a big investment fund could push a billion dollars through the
market.
The impact of larger flows on the currency market was highlighted by a
report by the Bank for International Settlements - the central bankers' bank
 -this week. It said turnover in foreign exchange increased 42 per cent
between 1989 and 1992 to an estimated Dollars 880bn (Pounds 620bn) per
business day in April of last year.
Much of that increase is not matched by a similar expansion of world trade.
More specifically, the BIS says that non-bank trade in the currency market
has grown. 'Transactions with other market participants have expanded more
rapidly than those between dealers,' the report says.
There are signs that these huge flows are changing the nature of foreign
exchange dealing.
There has been a greater concentration of business in London, the main
currency trading centre, because it can provide the huge pools of liquidity
that investors seek. London increased its share of the world's FX turnover
from 25 per cent in 1989 to nearly 30 per cent in 1992. According to the
BIS, there are now more dollars and D-Marks traded in London than in the US
or Germany.
There is a growing concentration of business among a decreasing number of
banks. Only the biggest banks can convince customers they have the financial
muscle to carry the liquidity and credit risk involved in large-scale
trading. The Bank of England reported last year that the 10 most active
banks in the City of London had 43 per cent of turnover, up from 36 per cent
in 1986.
The US dollar is losing some of its dominance as a reserve currency to the
D-Mark. The D-Mark has overtaken the yen as the second most widely traded
currency, being involved in 38 per cent of all currency deals. Mr Neil
MacKinnon of Citibank in London says: 'The growing use of the D-Mark
reflects the internationalisation of investment opportunities and the
greater importance of European bond markets.'
Do these developments matter? There are grounds for thinking they will
present new challenges to businessmen, politicians and central bankers.
Mr David Clark, European Treasurer at HSBC Holdings in London, believes new
participants will find it increasingly difficult to get into the market. 'I
expect to see smaller market participants trying to deal in newly
convertible currencies like the Hungarian forint,' he says.
London's growing dominance may also make it difficult for banks to develop
foreign exchange operations in any other European centre.
Mr Paul Chertkow, global currency strategist at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, says
this should concern politicians thinking of putting a European central bank
outside London.
'The BIS report shows that London did extraordinarily well even though it
was outside the ERM for part of the three-year period,' he says. 'The
decision to put the European central bank somewhere other than London would
be a nonsense given the primacy of the UK capital in foreign exchange.'
But for central bankers wishing to control exchange rates through
intervention, the sheer size of the market must be the biggest concern.
Mr MacKinnon says: 'If domestic economic policies are wrong - as they have
been in Europe recently - the currency markets play a useful role in forcing
central banks to adapt their policies.'
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MKTS  Market data.
    TECH  Services.
</TP>
