<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Queens Moat banks launch inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRANT Thornton, the accountants, were appointed yesterday by Queens Moat
Houses' banks to investigate why the hotel group has run into financial
difficulties.
The banks have asked for a report in seven days from Grant Thornton's
investigators, who went into Queens Moat's offices at 8.30am yesterday.
A full meeting of the hotel group's 45 banks, led by National Westminster
and Barclays, will be held as soon as the initial report is completed,
probably at the end of next week.
A banker said one of the main issues for the banks was whether Queens Moat's
senior management should be changed. 'I have never known a corporate crisis
erupt so quickly,' he said. Another banker said he had no inkling that the
group was in difficulties until Queens Moat suspended its shares on
Wednesday. 'The group has given no cogent explanation for why its finances
have deteriorated so rapidly,' the banker said.
Queens Moat has debt of more than Pounds 1bn, including an off-balance sheet
exposure which at the end of 1991 was Pounds 133m.
Banks are uncertain whether Queens Moat's financial difficulties are purely
the result of a change in its accounting policies or whether there has also
been a sharp deterioration in trading. 'We are not even certain whether the
group made a profit or loss last year,' one banker said. 'We will have to
wait to see what Grant Thornton says.'
The group's competitors believed that Queens Moat had been trading well in
the UK and that its market share had been holding up. At the end of 1991,
Queens Moat had 103 hotels in the UK and 86 hotels in Germany, the
Netherlands and other parts of continental Europe.
The group has to repay Pounds 658m of its debt within the next year. Until
the shares were suspended, the banks had been working with the group on a
plan to roll-over the debt. That plan will now be reviewed.
Bankers said they would probably insist that Queens Moat comes up with a
plan to reduce debt by selling assets.
Barclays and National Westminster have the biggest loans to Queens Moat, of
more than Pounds 80m each.
Holders of the company's Pounds 215m 10 1/4 per cent debenture stock, due an
interest payment totalling Pounds 11m yesterday, were relieved to receive
their cheques.
Bass, the UK brewing group which owns the Holiday Inn chain, yesterday
dismissed the possibility that it could emerge as a buyer of a large number
of Queens Moat hotels, but said it might be interested in buying selected
hotels to aid growth in specific markets.
</TEXT>
