<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Costain doubles pre-tax loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COSTAIN Group, the heavily indebted UK construction and mining concern,
doubled its pre-tax losses to Pounds 148.6m last year and again passed its
final dividend.
Had it reported under the FRS 3 accounting standard, which forces
extraordinary losses above the line, the pre-tax deficit would have exceeded
Pounds 200m.
Net assets at the end of December were cut to Pounds 75m, breaching banking
covenants. Mr Peter Costain, chief executive, said this would be rectified
by the sale of its Australian coal mining business to Hanson, pushing pro
forma net assets up to about Pounds 160m. The sale was worth Pounds 198m to
Costain - Pounds 157m in payment for the business and Pounds 41m in debt
relief. The way was cleared for the disposal less than two weeks ago when an
out-of-court settlement was reached with Hanson's Peabody subsidiary.
Wrangles broke out last autumn when Costain entertained a rival bid from
Altus Finance, part of the French bank Credit Lyonnais.
Mr Costain said a consortium of banks, led by NatWest, were being supportive
and the group had adequate working capital until March 1995. Net debt rose
from Pounds 125m to Pounds 331m last year. The main factors were Pounds 56m
of borrowings brought on to the balance sheet for the Spitalfields site in
the City of London, and the Pounds 58m impact of adverse currency movements.
Debt had increased by Pounds 67.1m since the end of the year. This followed
seasonal outflows of cash in the engineering and construction division, more
cash absorbed by the Channel tunnel contract and a further negative currency
effect of Pounds 21.6m.
Mr Costain said the up-to-date net-debt figure, taking account of the sale
to Hanson, was about Pounds 210m. 'We are seeking to reduce that by
disposals.' These might bring in Pounds 50m this year.
Operating profit fell from Pounds 27.4m to Pounds 2.9m on reduced turnover
of Pounds 1.24bn. Interest costs were Pounds 18.2m, compared with Pounds
23m. Exceptional charges totalled Pounds 133.3m, mainly for write-downs in
the value of housing land, commercial property and mining assets.
Mr Costain said Pounds 19m of annual costs had been taken out of the
businesses. The workforce had been cut by 1,100 to 4,300.
One bright spot was the international order book which had grown to Pounds
177m by February compared with Pounds 49m a year earlier.
Details, Page 18
</TEXT>
