<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Rail strike forecast to cause 'bedlam'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAIL WORKERS, miners and some London bus crews strike today in the biggest
burst of co-ordinated public sector industrial action in recent years.
The 24-hour rail strike will cause the greatest disruption, with the
Automobile Association predicting 'traffic bedlam', particularly in the
capital.
London Underground workers are not expected to join in the action, although
about 20 Tube stations, where tracks are shared with British Rail, could be
closed.
Mr Steven Norris, transport minister for London, warned drivers not to bring
their cars into the capital unless they were sure of a parking space.
The Confederation of British Industry said employers expected staff to 'make
every effort to get into work if they can', using alternative means of
transport - including car-sharing, cycling and walking.
Many companies would be arranging coaches and allowing flexible starting and
finishing times, said the CBI. The Institute of Management has suggested
working from home.
The strikes have been timed to coincide with a day of action by the European
Trade Union Confederation. British union representatives will join EC unions
in a march through Brussels.
Mr Norman Willis, who is president of the ETUC as well as general secretary
of the Trades Union Congress, said the protest was 'aimed at focusing public
attention across Europe on the evils of mass unemployment, unacceptable
working conditions and the growing threats from racism and xenophobia'.
To comply with the law against secondary strike action, all the participants
in today's stoppages are emphasising their individual grievances with their
employers. The National Union of Mineworkers was the first group to go for a
strike today and production at many pits ceased last night as about 30,000
walked out.
The NUM believes that it can still stop privatisations and closures by
mobilising public support.
About 68,000 members of the Rail, Maritime and Transport union are striking
because BR is refusing to guarantee that there will be no compulsory
redundancies. It is understood that BR management could take a much harder
line over any future industrial action.
About two thirds of red London buses are expected to be off the roads in a
dispute about longer working hours and cuts in pay.
