<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / The Lex Column: Next
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Next provides a graphic illustration of the rewards that stem from running
an extraordinarily badly-managed business half-way well. Two years ago, Next
recorded a net loss of Pounds 223m. Last year it made pre-tax profits of
Pounds 39m. It is easy to see how Next became the City's favourite recovery
stock. But the natural question is: what next?
The company's balance sheet has certainly been transformed. Operationally
too, Next has made giant strides. By rationalising its irrational store
portfolio and cutting its outlets from 450 to 305, Next has boosted
efficiencies. Sales per sq ft have risen 40 per cent over the past two
years.
The company's trading momentum, with sales currently running 12 per cent
ahead, should permit further gains. Sourcing, stock control and service have
all improved significantly but still lag best industry practice. This should
provide further headroom for profits growth without the company having to
resort to anything silly by way of acquisitions.
Next is certainly not going to repeat its spectacular share price
performance of the past year. A sub-market forward rating seems grudging
nonetheless. The same could be said for the whole retail sector which has
been looking forlorn of late.
Results from Kingfisher, Argos and now Next point to consumer spending being
healthier than expected. With costs pared to the bone, operationally-geared
retailers should register strong profits gains on even small sales
increases.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Next.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P5611 Men's and Boys' Clothing Stores.
    P5621 Women's Clothing Stores.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
