<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / The Lex Column: Currencies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bundesbank's reluctance to cut its official interest rates at
yesterday's council meeting is clear confirmation of its gradual approach to
monetary relaxation. That is not only baffling in view of the 1 per cent
fall in German industrial output during February. It also sits uneasily with
the growing realisation on the other side of the Atlantic that the US
recovery slowed during the first quarter. The combination pushed the dollar
back below DM1.60 yesterday - and dollar weakness has a nasty habit of
exacerbating tensions in the ERM.
The obvious implication is that the relative calm which followed the French
elections may not last. While the Bundesbank is being so coy, the new French
government cannot engineer the sharp fall in interest rates needed to reduce
unemployment. Double digit real interest rates are also troubling Danish
voters in the run up to next month's Maastricht referendum.
These factors must be plain for the Bundesbank to see, but they do not loom
large in its thinking. Inflation remains higher than the bank would like but
it is a lagging indicator. The money supply trend has improved, and there is
no longer much sense in using interest rates to apply pressure on the wage
and budget front. With such a weak intellectual case for high interest
rates, it is curious that the Bundesbank should persist.
</TEXT>
