<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Personal View: Russia's window of opportunity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANATOLI B CHUBAIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today, the Russian economy is struggling under the combined effects of high
inflation, declining output, demilitarisation, political instability, and a
restructuring of virtually its entire industrial base. The transition to a
consumer-oriented market economy is creating economic and political turmoil.
Never before has so large a country attempted to recreate itself over so
short a time; there is no use understating the scale of the upheaval or the
enormity of the challenge.
Yet with little fanfare from abroad, Russia is now engaged in the most
sweeping effort to change its economy since Peter the Great built St
Petersburg, his 'window on Europe', nearly three centuries ago. Some 5,000
large and medium-sized enterprises are heading for privatisation as Russia
hurries to build a market economy based on private property,
entrepreneurship, and economic opportunity.
Last December, the first auctions for shares in privatised enterprises
began. By the end of this month, more than 700 enterprises will have entered
private hands, creating thousands of shareholders and property owners. The
process began last year with the distribution of a total of 150m
privatisation vouchers to every man, woman and child. Each voucher, with a
face value of Rbs10,000, can be exchanged at privatisation auctions for
shares in large enterprises until the last day of this year, when the
vouchers are set to expire.
At the first auctions, each voucher bought an average of 3.7 shares. Each
share has a face value of Rbs1,000, which corresponds to its historical book
value. The inflation-adjusted book value is probably 20-30 times higher. So,
on average, early-bird investors were able to exchange each Rbs10,000
voucher for shares representing Rbs74,000-Rbs110,000 worth of property.
The enterprises up for auction run the gamut from small, high tech companies
such as the microelectronics concern Eleks, in Vladimir, to Gornozavodsk
Cement in the Urals. All leading industries, from manufacturing to services,
from chemicals and food processing to textiles and jet engines, are
represented.
The early successes of Russian privatisation are a direct result of the
government's commitment to stand clear and let investors operate free from
bureaucratic meddling. To buy shares in privatised enterprises, investors
have only to show up at auction centres with vouchers in hand and place
their bids. There is a large and liquid market for vouchers on exchanges
found in big cities throughout Russia, ensuring that vouchers are easily
purchased in bulk.
Both Russian citizens and foreign investors may buy and sell vouchers and
participate in the auctions at any time and place. Both play by the same
rules. There are no elaborate regulatory barriers, no special fees, permits,
or conditions. With most enterprises offering 30 per cent of their shares
for sale at auction and no limit on the number of shares any single investor
may purchase, investors can acquire large stakes. And soon investors will be
able to bid for shares in enterprises anywhere in Russia from
computer-linked auction centres.
Meanwhile, hundreds of entrepreneurs have seized the opportunity offered by
Russia's privatisation law to launch mutual funds (called 'investment
funds') for purchasing shares in privatised enterprises. The funds offer
voucher holders a way to spread their risk over a portfolio of enterprises.
Foreigners are free to establish new investment funds or to invest in
existing ones.
Eventually, with the shares of thousands of enterprises available for
trading, the embryonic exchanges which have sprouted up from Moscow to
Vladivostok will finance new business formation, investment, and job
creation. With privatisation in effect bringing thousands of initial public
offerings to market this year, the time may not be far off when the Moscow
stock exchange will become a great magnet for international capital.
Russia's experiment with entrepreneurial capitalism faces daunting
obstacles. But few countries can match its combination of a highly-educated
workforce, a first-class science base, a far-flung communications and
transportation infrastructure, and vast reserves of untapped natural
resources. Nowhere is the potential for growth so great and barriers to
foreign investment in privatised enterprises so few.
With privatisation auctions under way almost continuously, a new Russian
economy is rapidly taking shape. When the auction centres close at the end
of this year, an historic window of opportunity for investors will close
with it. Only those who seized the chance to become charter shareholders
will reap the full dividends of Russia's new millennium of freedom.
The author is deputy prime minister of Russia in charge of privatisation
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
