<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Observer: Chief of speakers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
No one could accuse Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi, the redoubtable Zulu leader
in South Africa, of dereliction of duty. He has just finished delivering his
longest ever policy speech - so long it deserves a mention in the Guinness
Book of Records.
The South African chieftain started speaking to his Kwazulu legislature on
March 12 and finally finished earlier this week. He spoke on every weekday
and notched up a total of 90 hours without repeating himself. Members of the
Kwazulu legislative assembly gave him a standing ovation when he concluded
his address which included a 60-page discussion on Inkatha's constitutional
proposals for Kwazulu/Natal.
Members of the legislative assembly were allowed to absent themselves from
proceedings if they had very urgent business, so long as a replacement was
present to take notes.
So you thought the Maastricht debate was boring?
</TEXT>
