<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Letter: Why property factor may harm recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr CHRISTOPHER JONAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your leader, 'A question of confidence' (March 27), suggests that
growth in industry's output is the only plausible motor for recovery. My
experience of the fragility of confidence, gained from visiting all parts of
the UK in the past eight months, leads me to agree with you. But with one
caveat.
Industry will need to be able to raise the necessary working capital to
increase its capacity to meet any increase in demand. Recent research
published by the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors shows the degree
to which UK banks have relied on the security of commercial property to
support lending to commerce generally. With property values falling and
likely to continue to do so for some time, businesses (and particularly the
smaller ones) may have difficulty in raising the short-term facilities so
necessary now.
On a tour of the US in the past week I have found a different position
there. US banks appear more ready to base their lending on their own
judgment of the business prospects of their customers. In the US there is no
longer a correlation between property values and the level of lending to
industry, whereas in Britain this is very strong.
Thus US industry does not suffer from an artificial constraint on its
facilities resulting from movements in a market often far removed from its
own. The recovery you seek will require a substantial contribution from
smaller businesses.
UK banks have a vital role as the monopoly suppliers of capital to this
sector. We must hope that they will be able to separate their often unhappy
experiences in direct property lending from this critical role in the drive
for recovery.
Christopher Jonas,
president,
Royal Institution of
Chartered Surveyors,
12 Great George Street,
Parliament Square,
London SW1P 3AD
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
