FT  02 APR 93 / Letter: Sums not done properly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JAMES ABBOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, R M Bale (Letters, March 31) asserts that railways are alone among
transport forms in requiring a state subsidy.
He has not been reading his FT closely enough: your own Richard Tomkins
demonstrated ('For whom the road tolls' February 13) how the UK road system
demands a public subsidy at least four times that of British Rail, if the
sums are done properly and environmental costs, policing, National Health
Service treatment of accidents and so on are taken into account.
Nobody has asked the improvements to the M20 to the Channel Tunnel to show a
financial return; why expect the rail link to the tunnel to do so?
James Abbott,
editor,
Modern Railways,
Terminal House,
Shepperton TW17 8AS
</TEXT>
