<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Arts: Ricochet - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Are you, like me, a sucker for murder stories? If so, you will be happy to
see the following newspaper advert on the posters and programmes for Malcolm
Taylor's new play Ricochet: 'PERFECT murderer offers Pounds 10,000 to
equally perfect murderer. Box No 3049.' The advert has been placed by Lord
Qualtrop; but for what reasons? It is answered by one Inspector Sparrow; but
what kind of inspector is he? He is greeted by the butler Disraeli; and what
kind of butler is he? Which of the three is a killer? Who will get killed?
Surprise caps surprise caps surprise caps surprise. The audience laughs more
often than it squeals. What larks]
Bath's Theatre Royal is filled by an audience that wants larks of these kind
 -and wants to see Nigel Havers and Keith Barron. Like people all around me,
I left the theatre with my head buzzing with the play's circuitous
intricacies; and I make tactful efforts now to give none of them away. The
play often has comic lines of an exquisitely sinister nuance. The inspector
says to the butler, ''The butler did it.' Have you ever done it?' The butler
replies, 'That's for me to know, Sir, and you to discover.'
The second inspector says to a suspect 'I wouldn't try anything. I got
passed over for promotion this morning.' And yet I felt no concern for any
character onstage; worse, no great sense of suspense; worst, no awareness
that murder is evil. True, one character sometimes says that murder must go
punished because it wrecks the lives of the living - but this attitude does
not prevail.
A comedy is not much of a comedy if it does not take something seriously -
in this case, murder. And a thriller is not much of a thriller if it it is
mainly conceived as a you'll-never-guess-what-happens-next joke. The point
of Ricochet is merely to manipulate its audience. In this respect it
succeeds cleverly enough - though its plot will bear little scrutiny for
either probability or logic. But Sleuth and Deathtrap took murder more
seriously, and thereby were more riveting and more fun. Ricochet amounts to
nothing but gameplaying. The taste that leaves is unpleasant.
Part of the gameplaying - this is hard to explain without explaining too
much - involves the roles. If there were one reason I might want to watch
Ricochet again, it would be to re-examine the acting that leads up to the
big unmasking halfway through Act Two. Nigel Havers and Neil Stacy, as Lord
Qualtrop and Bulstrode, execute one piece of virtuosity each that is
impressive afterwards, once you know what it was. But at the time it is
actually rather laboured and indistinct.
Havers's role is otherwise the usual engaging Havers exercise in classy
charm. Out of practice as a stage actor, he shows no great mastery of stage
projection, dynamics or pacing, but will doubtless gain more authority with
further performances. I note also that he is one of the two directors of
Havahall Pictures, which co-presents this play. David Taylor directs. Keith
Barron gives a performance that is absolutely right for the play - deft,
convincing moment by moment in an ambiguous way, lightweight.
At the Theatre Royal, Bath, until April 3
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
