<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / People: Heavyweights within its aegis
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Frank Law, septuagenarian former deputy chairman of NFC who took over as
non-executive chairman of Aegis last September, has managed to persuade two
respected figures from British industry and finance to join the board of the
troubled media-buying agency that moved its headquarters to Paris last
summer.
The arrival of Sir Peter Thompson, ex-chairman of NFC and founder chairman
of ProShare - which aims to encourage wider share ownership - plus Sir Kit
McMahon, formerly deputy chairman of the Bank of England and chairman of
Midland Bank, marks an attempt to restore the reputation of the once
high-flying media stock, which, aside from its financial woes, has managed a
poor record of corporate governance.
Law points out that he was hitherto the only non-executive on the 10-man
board - the other nine directors being all either executives of the company
or representatives of the two major shareholders, one French and one
American. 'It was sometimes a little lonely,' he remarks.
Sir Peter (pictured right) he knows well. As a founder of the company that
became NFC, Law says he played a part in his promotion to chief executive of
what proved to be the government's most successful MBO. He met Sir Kit
through Midland Bank.
Rather than the board interviewing the candidates, Aegis' troubles meant
that it was McMahon and Thompson who were given the opportunity to grill
anyone they wished in the company, for however long - and on their own.
Meanwhile, last summer's move to France unsettled UK institutions, not least
because it removed Aegis from the jurisdiction of the Takeover Panel.
Hence one crucial task for the new directors, who join in May, will be to
help the company make up its mind how to address these institutional
concerns.
Given that Law is in his 78th year, there is also the question of who will
be the next chairman.
Analysts expect that Aegis, which reports on Tuesday, will unveil
restructuring costs for 1992 that will more or less cancel out operating
profits of some Pounds 50m.
The share price, roughly 120p a year ago, collapsed over the summer, and
dipped as low as 13p earlier this year. Yesterday it edged up 2p to 19p.
</TEXT>
