<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Technology: US puts the emphasis on quality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If the US is to compete with Japan and Europe, it must create a 'national
quality centre' to co-ordinate the dissemination of total quality management
technologies to industries throughout the country, the Washington-based
Council on Competitiveness said this week.
In a new report*, the Council said that although TQM is now widely
recognised in business as a national priority, individual corporations do
not have sufficient resources alone 'to meet the aggregate US demand for
quality education and information'.
The Council - whose members are drawn from industry, academia and labour and
who helped produce the Clinton administration's technology policy - said
Japan's Union of Scientists and Engineers (Juse) could serve as a model for
a new systematic approach to 'quality diffusion'.
Juse is a non-profit group of corporations which work together with leading
universities to promote quality improvement throughout Japanese industry.
With its extensive national network of companies, it conducts research,
promotes quality practices and provides training in quality to workers and
managers.
Ray Stata, chief executive of Analog Devices and a member of the Council on
Competitiveness Executive Committee, sees a Juse-like organisation as key to
accelerating US quality improvement.
The world economy is 'in the midst of a transition in which competition has
become more acute,' he said. 'To some extent, it's them - Japan and Europe -
or us. We must find more efficient technologies for handling human
resources.'
In Japan TQM is regularly deployed throughout the company; in the US this is
true in only a few firms. Japanese industry has ongoing national programmes
to raise quality consciousness in society; Juse's 'QC Circles' focuses the
activities of small groups of workers continuously improving and problem
solving.
The adoption of TQM techniques requires a significant change in US corporate
culture. US companies have learned from the Japanese example that they have
to work together. 'Ten years ago, in our company and in others, if we found
a new way of managing, we would consider that a trade secret,' said Stata.
'But US industry has never been in this kind of a jam before.'
* Catalyst for Change: Juse and Japan's national quality system. Available
from the Council on Competitiveness, 900 17th Street NW, Washington DC
20006. Tel. 202 785 3990. Price Dollars 12 plus Dollars 3.50 overseas
shipping or Dollars 1 domestic shipping.
</TEXT>
