FT  02 APR 93 / Technology: PCs obey the spoken word - Worth Watching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Personal computers which carry out spoken commands have largely proved
expensive and unreliable. Applied Voice Technologies (AVT), of London, has
developed a speaker- dependent system which can be used with Windows
software and costs Pounds 250 for the board, software and microphone.
By voicing words such as 'save' or 'exit' the user can work through commands
which would take several seconds to execute using the standard mouse.
VoiceServer can store 1,000 words for each user and can search a list of 300
words for any single window. AVT: UK, 071 454 1224.
