<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / People: Cullimore to exploit Naafi challenge
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Colin Cullimore, who ran the Dewhurst chain of butchers for more than 20
years, has become chairman of Naafi, succeeding Sir Malcolm Field, group
managing director of WH Smith, who has inhabited the voluntary post for the
past seven years.
'Originally there was no thought of my becoming chairman,' says Cullimore,
who is 61 and joined the board in 1984, 'as they would normally look for
someone younger.' But with the impact of Options for Change, under which
almost half the British soldiers stationed in Germany (Naafi's most
profitable area) are to return to the UK, the need was felt for an
experienced hand to guide the institution through one of the biggest changes
since its founding in 1921.
As well as his retailing experience, Cullimore, who served in the parachute
regiment in Cyprus and the Canal Zone in the mid 1950s, has kept close
contact with the Services.
Naafi, the official trading organisation of the Forces, which sees an annual
turnover of Pounds 430m, gets no money from the government - unlike the
situation in other countries - and aims to return a surplus (Pounds 16m last
year) to Service welfare funds.
'With a much more sophisticated customer base, there is actually no longer a
need for the Naafi in much of the UK,' says Cullimore, 'but there is a
desperate need for it in Benbecular or Northern Ireland.'
One way to make money - and support the loss-making welfare operations such
as Bosnia - will be to expand the nascent financial services division.
'Servicemen worried about anything from motor insurance to investing
redundancy money feel they can trust us. This is an area with tremendous
growth potential.'
</TEXT>
