<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Management: The side-effects of a 'cure-all' approach
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER LORENZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW management concepts, even including 'excellence' and 'total quality',
have caught on as fast and furiously as 'organisational re-engineering' -
otherwise known by the equally awkward labels of 'core process redesign',
'business re-engineering' and a dozen other permutations of the same six
words, depending on which consultancy you talk to.
But few concepts have been as misunderstood, or risk being as misapplied.
Nor has so much doom been purveyed about the possible employment impact of
any organisational innovation. One forecast last month was that
re-engineering could destroy as many as 25m US jobs, mainly in service
activities.
Contrary to the easily confused, but broader and more complex, concept of
'organisational architecture', the principle behind re-engineering is
straightforward.
Its US consultant-progenitors, Michael Hammer and James Champy, define it as
'the fundamental re-thinking and radical redesign of business processes to
achieve dramatic improvements in critical, contemporary measures of
performance, such as cost, quality, service and speed'.
The word 'radical' means what it says: re-engineering may use similar
analysis methods to the old disciplines of work and time study, or
'industrial engineering', but unlike them it does not cover the
simplification and improvement of existing processes.
Instead, it involves transforming an organisation from one based on separate
'functions' (or specialist departments) - such as product or service design,
engineering, manufacturing, marketing, service and accounting - to one based
on the processes which span most or all of these activities and disciplines.
Most consultants advise organisations to start by re-engineering processes
which take them: from the initial concept for a product or service to its
launch; from customer identification to initial order; from order to
delivery; from service inquiry to fulfilment; and from delivery to payment.
In academic terms, which are being purloined increasingly by the consultants
to help convey their message, re-engineering involves transforming part of a
business unit - and eventually the entire organisation - from its
traditionally 'vertical' structure to a 'horizontal' one.
US companies which have reached various stages down this track, despite the
myriad of political and other internal stumbling blocks, include Texas
Instruments, AT&amp;T, Motorola, Ford, Kodak and Hallmark Cards. Unlikely
partial practitioners in Europe include British Telecom and Lucas.
The reasons why re-engineering has surged to craze-like status over the past
three years are plain but numerous. They include:
Recessionary and other competitive pressures, especially to slash costs, but
also to increase value. If re-engineering promises anything, it is that an
organisation can be re-designed to do 'more with less' - or 'much more with
the same'.
It is the most effective way of making an organisation far faster on its
feet, and more responsive to customers and competitors.
It is the logical next step after 'delayering', 'down-sizing' and
'restructuring' a vertical organisation by conventional means - something
which many large US companies, and a growing number of Europeans, have
accomplished or initiated since the mid-1980s.
It promises an answer to the much-debated problem of stagnant service
productivity. In effect, the re-engineering craze is sweeping into offices a
concept which was tested by cross-functional teams in factories and product
development centres during the 1980s.
It responds to the belated realisation of top managers that fortunes were
wasted on data processing investment in the 1970s and 1980s. Companies
automated old, inefficient functional procedures, instead of first
abandoning many of them, redesigning the resy, and only then computerising.
Hammer shot to general prominence in 1990 with a Harvard Business review
article called 'Don't automate, obliterate'.
It is being driven by sales pressure from every type of consultancy as they
jostle to annex the same territory. The most desperate are those firms which
used to specialise in information technology, such as CSC Index. But
generalists such as McKinsey, which majors on 'core process redesign', are
also in there fighting.
Given the breadth of these influences, it is not surprising that
re-engineering is so widely misunderstood. Like excellence and quality in
the 1980s, it is being touted as both a cure-all and what Hammer calls, in
American franglais, a 'term du jour'. He resents especially the use of it to
embrace delayering and down-sizing. 'Some companies say they've
re-engineered when they've done nothing of the sort - they've simply lopped
off part of the business,' he complains.
In many cases, re-engineering creates no net job losses at all, he says;
instead, its prime objective is to slash 'cycle time' or to raise quality.
But in other instances it can remove between 50 and 75 per cent of the jobs
in a particular process, 'though not in the total organisation'.
At CSC Index, Tom Waite dismisses the 25m US jobs scare as 'beyond the
realms of possibility' if his consultancy's experience with clients is any
guide.
His analysis, and Hammer's, is a partial corrective to the jobs horror story
 -unless one really expects companies to 'go horizontal' from bottom to top,
and to create no extra value or jobs, however indirectly.
There is certainly much talk in US companies of functional bosses
transforming themselves into new 'process owners'. But the realities of
executive life make one sceptical. Re-engineering is a juicy but tough nut
to crack.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management.
</TP>
