<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Row erupts over further 5,000 Navy
job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A POLITICAL row erupted at Westminster last night over the disclosure that
the Royal Navy will be cut by 5,000 more personnel than originally planned
in the Options for Change defence review.
Mr Archie Hamilton, the armed forces minister, said in a written reply that
the further cut of 5,000 would be partly achieved through redundancies of
about 2,300 next yearbut precise numbers and details had yet to be
determined.
'We will be encouraging the maximum number of volunteers, although some
compulsory measures may be needed in order to achieve the proper balance of
manpower within the Royal Navy,' he said.
The Ministry of Defence said last night that the further cuts were now
'unavoidable' as part of a continuing review of numbers beyond the review,
which is due to be completed by the middle of the 1990s.
Opposition politicians reacted angrily to the announcement. Dr David Clark,
the shadow defence secretary, said: 'It is disgraceful that the government
has sneaked out these figures in the fag-end of parliament.
'This form of crisis management actually threatens our defence capability.
What we really need is not a salami-cut approach to defence but a full-scale
defence review so we can see what is needed to defend British interests and
we can make provisions for that.'
Mr Menzies Campbell, Liberal Democrat defence spokesman, said: 'The defence
policies of this government are now in tatters.
'Cuts are being made without rhyme or reason. The only motive is to save
money to meet Treasury targets.'
He called for a full-scale defence review 'before Britain becomes a defence
laughing stock'.
The MoD said Options for Change, announced in 1991, envisaged two or three
phases of redundancy to reduce total numbers from 63,000 to 55,000 by the
mid-1990s.
Mr Hamilton said that the third phase of redundancies had been
'foreshadowed' last year and he was simply confirming it.
The MoD added that the 2,300 redundancies announced last night were needed
because the cut to 50,000 could not be achieved wholly through natural
wastage, reduced recruitment and other measures to control numbers.
</TEXT>
