<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Strikes pose little threat to economy: As commuters across
Britain face widespread disruption, FT writers assess the strategies of the
unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWENTY years ago a one-day strike by the main rail and mining unions,
boasting a combined membership of about 500,000, would have sent shudders
through the economy.
Today the combined membership is closer to 100,000 and, aside from the
considerable inconvenience to rail commuters, the one-day strikes will have
little economic significance.
Less than 10 per cent of domestic freight is now carried by rail and the
coal stockpile is 11m tonnes, more than a quarter of the coming year's
contract with the electricity generators.
The unions, aware of the limited impact of their action, cite the official
reason for today's disruption as the European Trade Union Confederation's
day of action against unemployment.
Unofficially, however, today is the closest that the more traditional
sections of the British labour movement can get to a general strike against
unemployment and pit closures.
Leaders of the National Union of Mineworkers still believe pit closures and
privatisation can be stopped by mass action supported by sympathetic public
opinion.
Mr Ken Capstick, leader of the Yorkshire NUM, says: 'We don't have the
industrial muscle any longer and we rely on popular support and on other
sections of the trade union movement. But in a strange sort of way the
miners can still give the lead.'
The RMT rail union appears to accept that privatisation is unstoppable but
wants to cushion members from the effects.
Its low-key campaign has failed to win the public support that it achieved
during the 1989 rail dispute but it has forced the government into
abandoning plans for a radical restructuring of the British Rail pension
fund.
The official reasons for action today are that BR is refusing to give a 'no
compulsory redundancy agreement' and refusing to abandon the use of private
contractors on traditional railway work. But the RMT executive also wants to
show solidarity with the NUM, especially because many of the 20,000 job cuts
expected at BR are linked to pit closures.
Laws on industrial action, however, mean the RMT may only take action
against its own management.
The NUM won 60 per cent support on a 75 per cent turnout for the action and
the RMT got 70 per cent support on a 55 per cent turnout. Both have talked
about further action but no firm decisions have been taken.
The RMT, in particular, might face a much tougher reaction from BR and even
from the government if it does attempt another strike.
Whatever the outcome of today's action and the threat of further disruption,
the important future battles will be fought in the law courts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
