<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Check urged on low audit fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUDITORS who undercut their competitors' prices will have to prove that they
have complied with professional standards under new draft ethical rules.
Those indulging in 'predatory pricing' or 'lowballing' - quoting fees
substantially lower than those of other firms - must ensure that the client
has a full description of the services to be covered and the basis on which
the fee will be determined for current and future years.
The details come in draft guidelines from the chartered accountants' joint
ethics committee, which covers the professional bodies in the UK and
Ireland.
A consultation process started last summer after concern about a number of
high-profile cases in which auditors had won tenders at substantially lower
rates than the existing audit fee.
These included Price Waterhouse's successful bid for the Prudential audit,
which appeared to reduce the audit fee by more than Pounds 900,000, although
it later emerged that three other large audit firms had tendered similar
bids.
The joint ethics committee stopped short of introducing restrictions on the
levels of audit fees charged. 'We decided not to muck about with the
market,' said Mr Jock Worsley, its chairman.
The consultation prior to the draft paper showed little evidence that
undercutting led to lower standards, nor that reduced fees discouraged firms
from conducting research and technical development.
It did highlight the fact that low fee quotations might result from more
efficient use of staff or other management actions.
</TEXT>
