<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Sale move over atomic agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Atomic Energy Authority took a step closer to privatisation yesterday as
the government announced that it was commissioning a report on the
practicability of moving the nuclear and industrial research agency into the
private sector.
This fresh evidence of the government's determination to press ahead with
privatisation was welcomed by the authority, which now operates under the
name of AEA Technology under an increasingly commercial management.
The business has changed substantially since the authority was set up in the
1950s to create a civil nuclear power programme. AEA has found markets in
new, non-nuclear fields, such as the transport and aerospace industries.
Since 1986 the agency has operated as a trading fund and sees privatisation
as a natural next step. Last year it made a profit of Pounds 28m on a
turnover of more than Pounds 400m.
The main question mark over privatisation is what should happen to the
agency's nuclear liabilities, covering radioactive sites such as the
Dounreay fast reactor on the north coast of Scotland which is scheduled to
stop operating next year.
The liabilities are estimated to amount to Pounds 3bn to Pounds 4bn and the
AEA is keen that they should be left behind in the public sector.
Mr Tim Eggar, the energy minister, told MPs that he was appointing
independent consultants to advise on the main ways in which this could be
done. Their report is expected in the autumn.
The AEA will be pressing the argument for being privatised as a single
entity.
Making the announcement, Mr Eggar referred to the report of the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission last May which urged a further review of strategic
options, including removing the AEA's business activities from the public
sector.
</TEXT>
