<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Call for single broadcast regulator
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Independent Television Commission said yesterday that the government
should consider a single regulatory body for all British broadcasting.
The commission, the regulatory body for commercial television, proposed in a
policy document sent to the government on the future of the BBC that the new
body should replace both itself and the BBC board of governors.
It said the intersection and overlapping in the jurisdictions of a number of
different bodies was 'already a source of serious confusion and concern'.
The commission also suggested a clearer line of separation between the
responsibilities of BBC governors and management, and that the governors
become a separate body with their own support staff. The licence fee could
be paid to the BBC via the governors on the basis of an agreed corporate
plan.
The BBC should continue to provide a wide range of programmes, it said, but
the corporation should not be allowed to extend its activities further - for
example into city-based local television.
