<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / World Trade News: Korea concedes over telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE CLINTON administration this week demonstrated the tough stance officials
have been threatening when US trading partners fail to keep trade
agreements.
In reviewing a 1992 agreement with Korea over telecommunications, they
discovered that Korea had failed to institute, as promised, 'a completely
transparent and non-discriminatory procurement system' for Korea Telecom,
the monopoly telephone company, and that it only made public regulations
which were no longer applicable.
Furthermore, US telecommunications companies, having been promised a fair
opportunity to bid on government contracts, were facing a complete exclusion
from the market for network switching.
During two days of talks from Tuesday, Mr Mickey Kantor, US Trade
Representative, backed by the entire administration, threatened to cite
Korea for violating a trade agreement and to announce sanctions.
'Korea said it would rectify the situation,' he said in a press briefing.
'It will make public all relevant regulations, and it guaranteed there will
be no delay in publishing regulations in future.'
Promising again not to discriminate, Korea has now put AT&amp;T of the US on the
list of companies qualified to bid for a contract worth at least Dollars
30m.
He said the US also would insist that Japan honour agreements made last year
to increase the purchase of US motor vehicle parts and raise the domestic
content of vehicles produced by Japanese companies in the US to 70 per cent.
Japanese officials are portraying the agreements as between US and Japanese
companies, and therefore not binding on the respective governments.
</TEXT>
