<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Manufacturing growth slows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US MANUFACTURING industry is still expanding, but the pace of growth has
slowed since the start of the year, the National Association of Purchasing
Managers reported yesterday.
The Purchasing Managers Index fell for the second month running in March to
stand at 53.4 per cent, the lowest level since October. This was well above
the 50 per cent threshold which indicates growth in the sector but sharply
lower than January's 58 per cent.
The greatest weakness was in export markets: in March the sub-index for new
export orders fell below 50 per cent for the first time since the
association began collecting export data in 1988, 'reflecting the slowing in
the economies of our major trading partners'.
The overall index is based on a survey of 300 companies and is regarded as a
reliable indicator of trends in manufacturing.
Mr Robert Bretz, an association spokesman, said there were 'encouraging
signals for continued moderate growth in the economy'. Within the
manufacturing sector 16 of 20 industries reported growth last month. The
average level of the index in the first quarter, moreover, was well above
the average for 1992, which saw a significant rise in gross domestic
product.
However, said Mr Bretz the rate of growth of production appeared sharply
lower than in February. Growth of new orders was also declining.
The fall in the purchasing managers' index follows a number of mildly
discouraging economic reports, including confirmation this week that the
post-election surge in consumer confidence late last year has largely
evaporated.
</TEXT>
