<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Brazil's deficit undermines IMF pact hope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAZIL'S Congress approved the federal budget for this year late on
Wednesday, after the most tempestuous negotiations of recent times.
But government officials are forecasting a budget deficit of the equivalent
of Dollars 10bn, which would destroy hopes of a new accord with the
International Monetary Fund or any early reduction of inflation, now at 27
per cent a month.
The Treasury showed a deficit of Dollars 400m last month - the first for
more than two years and underlining the parlous state of the country's
finances.
Also, the Dollars 234bn budget, formulated last August, includes no
provision for a court-ordered 147 per cent increase in state pensions, for a
newly approved 33 per cent wage rise for government employees, or for
President Itamar Franco's declared campaign on poverty.
The main expense is service of the government's Dollars 136bn domestic debt.
This will consume 65 per cent of the budget. Analysts say that the primary
surplus of 2.1 per cent of GDP last year was achieved largely by deferring
such as public sector pay rises, pension increases and infrastructure
repairs.
Mr Mailson da Nobrega, a consultant and former finance minister, says there
is 'no longer any disguising the fact that the state is bankrupt. Compulsory
expenses alone consume more than revenues.'
Under the 1988 constitution, the federal government has little leeway, 90-95
per cent of the budget being consumed by compulsory transfers of taxes to
the various states and municipalities, and federal employees being protected
by guarantee of tenure.
New taxes seem to be the government's only recourse, although a newly
approved tax on cheques has already been weakened and is expected to raise
only Dollars 4bn - less than half original predictions.
Mr Eliseu Resende, the new finance minister, says he expects no reduction in
inflation until October, when he hopes for a constitutional amendment to
allow fiscal reform.
</TEXT>
