<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / N Korea nuclear dispute goes to the UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL pressure on North Korea to co-operate with nuclear inspections
was stepped up yesterday when the International Atomic Energy Agency decided
to refer the case to the United Nations Security Council.
A two-day meeting of the IAEA's 35 governors in Vienna, which was forced to
take a vote on the issue, ruled that North Korea had broken an agreement on
nuclear safeguards. Mr Hans Blix, the agency's director general, is due to
report to the Security Council on the dispute in the next few days.
At the same time, the US, Britain and Russia issued a joint statement urging
North Korea to retract its announced withdrawal from the nuclear
non-proliferation treaty. The three countries, which are the depositaries of
the 1968 treaty designed to stop the spread of nuclear arms, said withdrawal
would be 'a serious threat to regional and international stability.'
They said it was in North Korea's interests to stay in the treaty and called
on it to comply fully with the safeguards agreement it signed with the IAEA
in January last year.
North Korea accepted six inspection visits before refusing access to two
facilities near its Yongbyon nuclear reactor complex. It has claimed they
are conventional military facilities.
However, experts suspect that the country may have used more nuclear fuel,
and may have been able to separate more plutonium for possible weapon use,
than it has declared.
Without powers of its own to take action, the IAEA could do little else than
appeal to the Security Council - the first time it has done so.
However, it is unclear what the Council will do. China, which along with
Libya voted against yesterday's IAEA ruling, is opposed to sanctions,
arguing that it would be counterproductive to isolate North Korea further,
and would be able to use its veto in the Security Council.
Moreover, the rotating council chairmanship passes next week to Pakistan,
which was one of four IAEA governing board members to abstain in yesterday's
vote. The others were India, Syria and Vietnam.
North Korea is considered still to be bound by the terms of the treaty,
which stipulates three months' notice for withdrawal.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>KPZ  North Korea, Asia.
