<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 93 / Kashmir rebel leader murdered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DR Abdul Ahad Guru, one of India's top heart surgeons and a prominent
supporter of the Kashmir rebellion, was killed yesterday, dealing a blow to
the government's plans to revive the political process in the state.
Dr Guru would have been a key figure in any attempt by the government to
negotiate with the militants, and his death yesterday will prove a strong
deterrent to any moderate voice in the state.
More than 12 people, including the dead doctor's brother-in-law, were later
killed when security forces opened fire on his funeral procession.
Small processions took to the streets defying curfew in some parts of
Srinagar, the capital, shouting anti-India slogans, and the mourners, for
whom killings by security forces and militants have become a daily feature
in the past three years, cried openly in the streets.
Dr Guru's body, shot at three times at close range, was found yesterday
morning.
He had been abducted on Wednesday by armed militants who hijacked his car as
he was driving to a meeting of the Supreme Revolutionary Command Council of
the militant Jammu and Kashmir Liberation Front of which he was one of the
main leaders.
The JKLF and other militant groups accused Indian agents of killing him.
Home ministry officials blamed the militants.
The government is preparing a series of measures to try to solve the
three-year crisis in Kashmir. It has replaced the discredited state governor
and plans other personnel changes to revive the defunct administration, as
well as economic grants and an amnesty for some prisoners.
There are also plans to grant an amnesty to Kashmiris in custody against
whom there are no serious charges.
In Srinagar, militants are openly derisive of the government's approach.
</TEXT>
